\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid14483652 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Could w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid725484\charrsid6557717 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 have your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 John Emrys Edwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I live in Nant-y-Neuadd Farm, Kenfig Hill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Are you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, I am married and I have four children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The year of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 We were married in - 1935.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And the year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I was born in 1903, on December the nineteenth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
I was born in the cottage at Pontrhydyfen, Port Talbot. The - all right, the - the - leave that - the cottage, or better known - or better known to the Pontyrhydyfen people as Tetocan.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well I was five - five years when - five years old when we - left the cottage to go and live in Oakwood, Pontrhydyfen which was across the river.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where did you live then, did you stay in Oakwood some time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
We stayed in Oakwood until 1923. And my father being a colliery manager - he moved down - to - the group of collieries of the Baldwins, Aberboydwin and Pintra collieries at Kenfig Hill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember why you moved from the cottage to Oakwood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, the cottage was - just as the thatched cottage of the time was. They had only - one long bedroom, where the parents and the children - slept, and there was one kitchen and what is called the chamber, the little room that was adjoining. And it cam
e when we - the family was coming, we were then - three children and my parents, and the building trade was going on at the time, and I can remember my mother telling me how she put the deposit of one pound on a house that was built, and - that - is known
 as Penhydd Street, Oakwood, Pontrhydyfen, and - that's where we lived until we moved to Kenfig Hill, in - 1923.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When you say you remember your mother telling you about putting the deposit, what did she tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The - interesting part about tha
t - was - that it was her brother was one of the contractors that was building - that was building the houses - for the other man was - Daniel Jones, he was the carpenter, and my uncle was the mason, Jenkin Thomas was the mason, so - she wouldn't - think 
of her - brother, but she did ask - Daniel Jones - what were the terms and how much of a deposit was wanted for a house, and he said, well - how much have you got? And it must have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid725484\charrsid6557717 
been - well, if you've got a po}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 und that is sufficient for the deposit on the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I had five sisters and - two brothers besides - two brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Could you give the birth order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh - I had five sisters - my - the eldest sister Eunice was born in September 1902. And 
then Irene was born in December the twenty-fifth, 1907. Rhoda was March - 1907. Then came the twins, Kitty and Megan, born in September 1911. Those were my sisters. I was the eldest boy born in 1903. Elwyn was born in June 1905. And then Thomas, the young
est of us, he was born on November the tenth, in 1912.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, twenty-seven. Father was twenty-seven when I was born, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He was born in Pontrhydyfen. He - never rememb
ers his father, his father came - strangely from the Kenfig Hill district, came to Pontrhydyfen when the iron works was going then in Pontrhydyfen - the iron works which - had the water for the big bridge. His father was a blacksmith, and by his photograp
h
 that we have, he was a six footer and a strong able man. The depression came in the - works in - at Pontrhydyfen at the time when Rhonda Blycombe works were opening, and so it seems he went there for a - to have work, and - received a damp bed which - br
o
ught on what we call today pneumonia, but then it was called inflammation. Mm. And he was - he died leaving a widow with two little children. Sister was older than my father. Things being very bad at the time - and it was very bad too - there two little c
h
ildren, but with the help of the family, and she - like many more, took in the washing and went to do washing, and - they - his upbringing was - as you can imagine, was not very good under those circumstances. Still - he had been brought up - Church of En
g
land, Church of England boy, and they were very devout, he knew his creed and he knew everything. And he - was with them until - as he explained, a lad of fifteen, and then he went to the non-conformist, because - as he used to say they had stronger food 
f
or him. They used to have - literary and debating societies which were very - popular at the time and he reveled in that. Always been a good reader, he - was up to date with the latest books. But not only that, he was a keen musician. And - even with his 
-
 lack of funds at the time, but he did go to Neath to take lessons on the violin, and one of his - fellow students, under a gentleman called Moodie, was - the late Doctor David Evans of - Cardiff. And I can remember Doctor David Evans - conducting the - a
 Gamanfu Ganu in Bridgend and coming to my father afterwards and say - where did you go out of my life, I thought sure that you would have come on with me. Well now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did your father do, what was his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well he was - there wasn't a thing i
n Pontrhydyfen at that time for any young man, except the collieries, and - we can hear many of the tales - of the - the colliery then, the lads were going, starting work - from ten to twelve, in these places on the mountainside, and - eventually - the bi
g
ger collieries came, they sank the - Whithworth pits in - in Ton Mawr, they were not the success, but then they sank the Cannon Pit. There was an old Cannon Level, but then they sank the pit, when the Percy Jacobs and his brother came to the Evan Valley. 
Many of the bigger collieries were started afterwards, such as the Frynrhnfar and the pit in Glyncroch, and Nant-Olaf, but the Oakwood there was - was about coming to an end at that time. But colliers, miners they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Your father went to work there did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. Aye, the - the - into the - into the collieries, there were - various I've named two or three different types but it was in the - Niguday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When did he start work there, at what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Ten, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did he have any other jobs then, he started in the colliery?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. Well now here's one - interesting point again. He was - he didn't have - there were no jobs, no second jobs at that time. But - he was - a keen radical pol - political - politically, and - S.T. Evans, the member f
or Mid-Glamorgan, he was the - a big man and a big friend of my father, and during election time I can remember the committee rooms in our parlour, and the comings and goings when I was a toddler during election time on - that time. When Lloyd George - in
t
roduced his - bill, my father was - very very much for that. And one of - that advocated - the insurance. He also was on the committee of a provident society, which I don't know if it's still going but it was until lately, the Bristol West of England and 
South Wales Provident Society. That did give - something like from eleven shillings to fourteen shillings a week if a person was ill. Another - thing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did your father have to do with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He was - at one time, he was secretary of it. And -
 but he was - as they had just a - a few, you had a secretary and a treasury - treasurer and just a few members of the committee, but he was always involved in that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He did that as well as his job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 As his job, yes. Another thing - that started a
t that time - was the Co-operative movement. And he with another - half a dozen, after they had done their work, they were going down - to this new - Co-operative, and they built it up until it was wrong enough to employ a secretary manager for it. So he 
was one of the - founders of the Co-operative.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He was a miner, did he have any other job then, was he always a miner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, he never were - was anything excepting the - in the coalmines. But what year are you going - I see what you are a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086728\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ming at. 
Having been brought up in the collieries, at that time there was - a movement for - the education that could be had, and - he took up - a correspondence lessons in the science and art of mining, and I can remember those - weekly - books - coming to the ho
u
se and he used to study those, and - mining and geology and insulation, and all those - until eventually, he became a fireman, and then - graduated from there to the - second class manager's certificate. And finally - at the age of twenty-one he qualified
 as a mining engineer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If he had his mining engineering certificate at twenty-one and he was born in 1876 it meant he qualified in 1897, as a colliery manager?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So he was a colliery manager before you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But actually he didn't continue with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He was still a collier, I say, but he was - cutting coal up until - 1911, 'til the 1912 strike. 1912 strike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But you told me earlier he went to do a colliery manager's job earlier?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So in 1911 he was still in the mines as an ordinary miner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
After the 1912 strike - that he - saw the advantages of using his certificate and at that time became a fireman, and later he became an over}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086728\charrsid6557717 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 man, and - later - he took up again - the colliery manager}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086728\charrsid6557717 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
ship, in Ton-y-Banwen. Ton-y-Banwen colliery up in Ton Mawr. In 1923 - he - we moved down, he became a - the manager of the Baldwin's group of collieries in Kenfig Hill, Aber-Byden and Pintra colliery. Which at that time employed over a thousand men
. And - unfortunately he - he developed - an illness that he - died when he was forty-eight. I don't know what's your next question but if -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember him ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. They - only in the period of - the period of 1912 strike
. He was all miners were out of that time. And it was a - bitter struggle which - oh he had the young family, growing family at the time, and it was after the 1912 strike that he - decided - to - although - he would be earning less money as an official th
an he could as a miner, because he was - a specialist miner, that is - he was - a heading man. There was a group of our that were - working headings, which had - a big advantage over the colliers that were in - the top holes as we called them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What was the advantage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
The advantage was then that the - the - oh the ordinary collier that was working with his mate or with a boy in the top hole was that they only had - the coal they cut, whereas the heading men, they were paid yardage because they had 
to - clear the - the muck as it was called, the shale, and also they were paid for the double timber that they put. They were also paid for the rails that was going along the heading was the main gallery. So that the heading man - the heading people had t
hose advantages, yardage, timber and the rails.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I asked you whether he had any part time or casual jobs, he didn't really have any paid work did he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, there was - no the - the payment was so much, he used to go to - I remember going with him, 
going to the - like the monthly meetings or the district meetings, and it would be down in Neath. He was paid his expenses, for going to - a - conferences and so forth, but apart from that I don't think that it was any - any big advantage to him - financi
ally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 We worked it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 She was - a native of Pontrhydyfen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Had she any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Never anything except a housewife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did she work after she was married or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No part time jobs? But you did say that when your father died, did she work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, she did not. We - this - this note might be of - of - one of the disadvantages of the - a colliery manager - was that he - was 
in - the colliery house. Aberboyden and Pentra collieries, they housed their officials all together in one group known as the Oaks. Well the colliery manager, once he was disposed - or - died, another was coming in for - straight away. So that we exchange
d
 - houses with someone from Kenfig Hill, and - another manager came - to tak his - place. My mother - with - the help of my eldest sister who was - in business - and my brother and myself, we - did the best we could to - maintain the family, and rememberi
n
g that there was five - younger ones, who had started a grammar school career - I can't remember - that there was any difference - in the table, not what we wore on our backs, nor our mode of living. My mother kept us together. The - twins - they decided 
a
fter having their - passing their - higher it was called then, the - what was the examination, junior and senior, after - after having their senior exam they decided that they would take nursing as a career. And they were both accepted - to do their train
ing in the General Hospital in Birmingham. Mm. Father was a manager up in the Oaks.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Can you remember how many rooms were in the house at Oakwood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, there were three - rooms upstairs. Three bedrooms. And - there were three rooms downstairs, an
d - a - a - scullery, a scullery we called it. We did have - running water, in a tap, and we did have - I remember the time when the sewer was put in. That was - it came - it wasn't there with the - when the houses were built. I have mentioned that the de
p
osit of one pound was placed on the house in Penhydd Street, but when we remember that the total outlay was two hundred and fifty pounds - thinking of terms today well that was going back - I did remember my mother saying that her parents - were able - to
 - go - as mortgages for part of the money, but it took a long - many many years to - wipe off the debt gradually, but eventually - it was - and became - afterwards, a very very good investment for my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did anyone else live in the house besides your parents and your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No other relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No other rel -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Or lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Occasionally when - I'm looking back at it, when - as - as the babies 
