maker was Miss Thomas Mrs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12086728\charrsid6557717 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 Price afterwards, Tom Price's wife, and after she finished we had this Miss Jenkins. And as John my brother said his job was to carry the machine. And - we used to love to see her coming because we had a lovely fire in the middle 
room, and my mother had a lovely - thing that she used to put the toast on, and that's what I can remember about the dressmaker, was the lovely tea we were having you know with this toast and butter all streaming down. And this dressmaker, she used to lov
e to come to our - my mother's house because she used to say, well I've never tasted such nice food as Mrs Edwards cooks. That's - quite true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father help your mother at all with any jobs around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, I'm afraid not, it was - a 
comparatively new house when we went there, which - didn't in - as far as I can remember require any - any jobs to be - done to it. And - I'm afraid that - he wasn't very domesticated, and - I have followed suit. He had a good mother, that did everything 
for him. He afterwards had a very good wife that - did everything for him. And I followed, I had a good mother and I had five good sisters, and I never did anything at all - my - wife now tells me that - I was spoilt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When you were a little boy did you have any jobs to carry out in the house? Regularly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not in the house. He used to work for money - for money outside the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about in the house, did you have anything your sisters had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, John my brother never worked. He - he didn't clean the brass or the knives and forks, like Elwyn and I had to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well he was never in. John my brother was never in, he was always out. But - Elwyn and I, we - we were the ones that helped my mother, cleaning the brass fender and cleaning the candlesticks, cleaning the knives and forks. But as for my elder brother, no.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did you think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well, we didn't think anything about it. We just took it you know that it was - he was cut out to be out, but 
there was an occasion when he was in the house one night, and my parents had gone to - the Thanksgiving, chu - in the church because my father was a churchman at the beginning, well the three of us were left in the house. So John thought now well he could
 
smell sweets - up in the top cupboard. And he thought it was easy, there was a fireguard - and from the chair onto the fireguard, his foot on the next shelf and up to the top to the sweets, and lo and behold the poor boy fell down, and the kettle of boili
n
g water was on the hob, that fell into the fire and all this stuff came on his leg and burnt him until he nearly - do you know that was a terrible night. And - well he had the doctor, and it wasn't boiling water, it was this - the heat, that was coming ou
t of the fire came on his leg. Just because he was one of those type of boys. \{BLANK\}
 And I couldn't get out of between the guard, I fell in through the guard, caught me then you see. Well now last night I was looking at that, and - there you can see now how that - how much of it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father make the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, everybody - everybody - the - the first down, the first down - lit the fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But he'd do it on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. But - to say about - fire - I don't remember that as it w
as, as it is today. Because when you think that every miner at that time was having a load of coal every month, that means that he was having twelve loads of coal and the coal of the Eben Valley was noted, and the last thing we did at night was to damp th
e fire down with small coal. That in the morning it was only just rake out the bottom, and you had the fire on, that the fire hardly went out -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your father do any cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would he ever wash up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. He had to - with eight children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would he do any decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
It's my mother would do the decorating. No, there - as I've said, there would be - it was a comparatively new house, and a well built house, and - that didn't need.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your father ever dress you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If necessary, yes, if - if the occasion a came that - my mother was indisposed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would he undress you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. And - as - as for John saying - that he was doing jobs in the house, it was my father
's job to bath the children on a Friday or a Saturday night. That was his job, to bath - us. That's right John?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The rest of the week who would bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh well we weren't bathed only once a week, we had a good wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So he bathed you really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It's my father was bathing us once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your father read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, he would read - I - it was at that time that - he - the - a series of books came, out - the first one was Door of the Heart. Door of the Heart, R.H. Hughes, U
pper Brighton. And he used to - well they were - short little poems, such as the - the Welshman, the Welshwoman in an English - hospital. And - was - that book, used to read those out, mostly I should fancy for my mother's sake, but I used to - I used to 
- and I can remember some of them now. Then that was followed by - Other Doors, and - eventually - all the doors drysau was made into one book, Poems by RH - R.H. Jones, Upper Brighton R.H. Nones, Upper}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12086728\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Brighton, that's the man and I've got that book, and I
 - go at it very very often. One of them I can remember then that - Come Dei amongst the flowers, Dei to see the little flower weeping. I have bruised it there are big tears on its cheeks, oh do you see Dai. That type was new that type of - poetry was new
 at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And your father would read it out loud would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
He would read it out loud that I - it was many years afterwards that I came to read it for myself, but they all - they all - they weren't new, they - had been -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would he tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh he was one of the masterpieces on the stories. And after this bathing time on a Friday night - we looked forward to the stories, and he used to tell us about our cousin Fritz, from Russia. And he used to go and bring us and the cousin F
ritz - was such a character he become one of us. And then when it would come that either this poor bear was coming or the wolf, he used to go - and make that noise till the younger of the family would be jumping out of their skin and my mother would turn 
t
o him and say, what are you frightening these children for? And with that, that was the end of the story, our cousin Fritz, and we'd have to go to bed until the next bathing night. Yes. But here's one instance of him as a reader. The - he was working - ni
g
hts in the Cannon colliery, and it had been a terrible night of storm, and the - men were coming up from Port Talbot the following morning, and everybody was talking about the - blizzard that had - raged, and the Port Talbot people said, oh nobody has sle
p
t in Port Talbot, because there's a boat come up on the Morva beach. And - that boat - they had saved - they had saved the crew. So I'm come home and had his breakfast and - bathed. There was a train that was going down, the - ten o'clock train, so - he m
u
st have asked my mother - have you got train fare for me to go down, I'm going down to see that boat. The Amazon, that was the name of the boat, and I believe it was in 1909 - well anyway my mother must have given my father - a yellow sovereign, that's al
l
 that she had. Well he went down and he saw the Amazon, and coming up in Port Talbot, and looking in the shop - a book shop, Days in Port Talbot, he saw a book that he always - wanted. It was the Em - the Essays of Emerson. And I still have that book, but
 
it is written on the front, bought on the morning of the wreck of the Amazon - 1909 I think is on it, and what I think is - happened - why that he autographed that, my mother must have asked him for the change, and that she was - seven and six short, and 
at that time that must have been a tremendous price for that, but I still have that book. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your father ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. The day war broke out in 1914 - my father had a cousin in Porthcawl - and Porthcawl in th
ose days from Pontrhydyfen was to us - that we were going to London. Well the day war broke out he took John and elwyan and I to Porthcawl to see his cousin. Who kept a pub. Yes, he did take us out without my mother, and that's the very particular day I c
a
n remember, because there were trains going through Porth station - we were going by train see, and there were trains going through the station, it was - well I don't think, we - I was amazed and - we were asking daddy, well what's this all about, and fla
gs outside the trains, and that's what I can remember, we are going - we are going to fight the bloody Germans. \{BLANK\} The garrison that was - the garrison that was down in Pembroke Dock at the time, they were the regular soldiers. They're going.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember your father taking you out other than that, would he take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, he had - in Cardiff again near there he had - an uncle in Cardiff, an uncle and an aunt in Cardiff, and - I can remember being taken with him, only a - to take - taken to Cardiff, and - what I can remember about that -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717  Cardiff to me was - well, fair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
yland at the time. But coming back through - Roath Park and my father talking with - the - gardener in Roath Park, and that gardener kindly - giving me -
 a few roses, in a little posy to take back to my mother. And the name of that rose which was the darkest rose o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 all, which was my father's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717 favorite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 and has been mine since it's - gone out of fashion now, but that rose was - Hugh Dixon. And Hugh Dixon was
 the most fragrant of all. But having come back by train to Port Talbot, we had lost the train to the Eben Valley, and - there was a late brake - going from the Walnut Tree Hotel in Aberavon, but it was only going as far as Cwmavon, and I can remember - w
a
lking and being carried late that night, and - up to Pontrhydyfen, and we had to - pass under those bridges, but there was a weir Gorad, and I still can remember the rumbling of that water - and that - impression - very young. Well I was being carried par
t of the way you know. Talking about Ivor Davis now - our neighbour, Mrs Griffiths who had - one child more than we had, she had nine child - nine children, and how they used to go having put the children to bed - one }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717  Mrs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Griffiths would tell the - my mother, come on, lets go down to see my sister Annie, says - which is Mr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717  Ivor Davis's wife, and there - they would go down there in - by the time they'd have walked down - have an hour down there and have a cup of tea and something to eat and walk back, but
 that was considered - a night out at the time, having to walk - well it would have been three miles and just a chat with somebody - because that was before - there was no - there was no cinemas there was nothing at all. All - entertainment - had to be ma
de.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your mother go out often like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Not so much - as far afield as Cwmarthen, but it was - yes, she would - once or twice a week go over to my grandmothers. And then my grandmother would come - well - once a fortnight, and that would b
e a memorable time for us children because - she would have this cape - this cape - beav}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13524052\charrsid6557717 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
r - cape, and underneath she would have called on the way - for - a pound of biscuits, and they were always the garibaldi, with the currants, and - she used to - dole those out to the children - every so often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I was asking you about little jobs you had to do in the house and your sister said that you didn't do any really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the older children, did they help the younger children with things they found difficult to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, the responsibility came on - it was expected of you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you have to dress them or help them to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 With the five sisters of course, no, they came - very simply they came to - when you are eight chil
dren it's the - the survival - of the fittest it is and there is no - I've no need - if somebody do - just mention that he didn't want something there was planty more that did want it and you wouldn't have the second chance, so they learnt, we all learnt 
very quickly. But it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would the younger children help the older in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, they - yes, they had to do - very much the - run errands, and - do some little jobs that were required.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your father look after you at all when your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, he would - it was only just a matter of - that there was somebody in the house. It's not a question of looking after because invariably - he would have his - always have his reading, if it wasn't a book, it was always a Goleuad - a
nd then he would have a - a - Cymro, the Faner, Faner and - the periodicals that were going. So he - that only just that he was around, but it was never as if it - he was - looking after anybody.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. That was - definite, the - it was the - thing done - that - when it would come for - I don't know about the younger ones, had to go - of course the girls, they were in a different category to the boys, but the boys were expected t
o be in - the house and in bed - by ten. That was the period - but 1914 - that changed - changed everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about when you were a little boy, when you were in school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh when I was in school the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What time would you have to go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
It all depended on the season. If it was the - winter of course well - it was the sun that decided when we went indoors and when we went to bed. Because there was such a variety of - everything to entertain you in the village at that time, you had 
the river, which in summer was - well that was our playground, either to try and catch a fish or - we would be after some tadpoles or frogs, and if it was warm enough we would be - swimming. And that every boy in the Avon Valley could swim very near as so
o
n as he could walk. So - then you had - the collieries had come, the - collieries had come by that time, and there was always colliery horses and stables which - brought us - we used to spend a lot of time down there - helping the ostler, and - if he woul
d
 give us a brush to groom the horses we were in our element. Those kind of - pastimes, that used to keep us - then again it would come - always if you wanted something extra - there was the Winbury time, and there was the blackberry time, and - very often
 you could have a spare copper by picking a jug of - either fruit for somebody who was unable to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 There were lovely winberries weren't there?
