\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about making pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Diodfaen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, diodfaen in summer always. The nettle - a spring of yarrow, and the - dandelions. And there wa
s another one or two herbs that would be - but as - lemon - lemon would - at the top of it. And then when we would have the - the yeast in - and that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717  was - well everybody made diod}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 faen at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You mentioned earlier that your father grew vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And some soft fruit, did they buy any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, we had to buy - there was the farmers and in that locality they still come around. There was an old lady from Hawdre Frm that used to come on a Saturday morning, sitting on a gambo, and -
 potatoes and turnips. She would - white turnips in season, swedes and potatoes. And we used to buy those from the gambo, and when she would have served us and they were out, that lady was so industrious she wouldn't waste, there she would be with her ste
el needles and she'd be knitting stockings or gloves - between calls - and weighing out the potatoes, but - those were the only vegetables that - because we were more or less self maintaining - for green}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 stuff.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about tinned vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Dried vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Tinned fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, on a Sunday. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you have any dried fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. Prunes, I can remember Prunes and apricots, dried fruit like - but I don't - can't remember anything more apart from that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you keep any livestock for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, there was - always - chickens. Always chickens. And when the war, 1914 war came out we had permission to keep a pig, down - below the house. And - there we - while the war and for a year or two afterwards, we did keep a pig.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who looked after the chickens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
The chickens were only a few yards from the - from the back door really, and there we had a cask and that was very convenient for the neighbours, so they wouldn't think they were wasting - 
if - a stale half a loaf or a crust would go in either to the pig or to the chickens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you children have to look after them or would your father or your mother look after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 All of us, we would just - the command would come - go and give
 - go and give something to the chickens, we would throw - some Indian corn and - we would get something from the cask and - there you are, it was just that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would look after the pig?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When we had a pig we had to go in turns, John and Elwyn. 
Or Elwyn and I. Or John and I. And to think we had to walk down a - a deep slope, and the pig sty was always near the riverside, and we'd go down there with a torch and this bucket of stuff to gove to the pig - about eight o'clock at night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But there were two of you always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Always - oh yes, both of us, and we three were together you see and then the - the other five were sort of colony - of their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And yet there was only two years between?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Of course the twins were self-sufficient?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, that's right. We three seemed to be - more - you know, bosses as it were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Bacon of course we had our own bacon - while the pigs lasted. There was meat of some part every day - 
and at the weekend, that would - weekend would always be - the - and it was - cig we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
ther - weather, it wasn't the lamb as we know it today. They used to kill the sheep, either they were bigger and they were older, but for a family such as ours you wanted - leg we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 a}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ther, and that was - there was cutting on that for a family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you ever have tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you ever get extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, now we're coming on to - yes, very - there was quite a - a lot -
 a few of those coming periodically because - I was - attached to a farm, and - that farm - had land on Margam Moors, and when we used to go to Margam Moors, if we were going mowing, invariably there would be a few of those rabbits who - who were - had th
eir legs chopped off by the mower and those we used to bring back. And - there were a few other - instances of - supplementing the menu - with rabbit, and an occasional hare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When you say you were attached to a farm what did you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well - that
's how I got attached to the farm. Two of our cousins at Penhydd Fach Farm were in the Territorial Army the - Royal Horse Artillery, and - in July of 1914 - they were on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 manoeuvres}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717  in Salisbury Plain. Their father kept the butchers shop - but those boys - 
did not return from Salisbury Plain, they were pressed on to go and they were about the first batch - that went to France. Both did return from the war, but - not until it was all over in 1918. Well - being interested in riding horses, I having had - a de
light for a farm, and another boy - Will Timpant, he had - farmers blood in him, so we both - kept the farm of Penydd - going. And we - were there cleaning out the sheds, feeding pigs - gathering the lambs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How often would you get extra meat from poaching or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well we used to get it as - periodical trips down to - down to the moors. It didn't come very often, but one - other - one other source was open to - to me, and that was - that there were sheep being killed on the line. No
w the - the village was between two railways, the Rhonda and Swansea Bay railway on one side, and the PPR, the Port Tabot railways the other side. Well the sheepsaw - the sheep of the farm I was attached to and other sheep - they would be coming down thes
e
 bridges of which there were five bridges, carrying these railways in the place, and sometime the sheep would be in - between those bridges, when a light engine or a coal wagon would come down and the next thing we know - knew that there was - a sheep, so
metime two and even half a dozen - had been killed - with these - train, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 luggage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 we used to call them. Well when the farmer would go - it was reported and when the farmer would go he'd have to - take those away, and sometimes a sheep would have been cut
 in half, and he would say, here you are - take this home with you, and - we would have the hindquarter of the two - of the two - of a sheep between the other boy and myself which used to eke out -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It was quite a help wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
It never was perceptible, but - I know - going to - the colliery - when I was a lad - I'd been - at fourteen - I'd been working underground for a twelve month, and 
I can remember one - very very - black week, everything - there was nothing at all to be had, and - to put in my box to go to colliery, except black bread - and boiled potatoes. And I remember my mother putting that box - for me that day, and the tears in
 
here yes, saying well this is all I've got for you, and - going then. But the following morning I thought well I'm going to change this, and I went on an old pushbike that I had down to Neath, I saw - a queue waiting for something and I joined the queue. 
A
nd when it came my turn it was a huge butt, with red herrings, and you were only allowed - one pound. And there was this man with a kind of a spade, and he was hacking at these and until he'd have a block, putting it on the scale somewhere near the pound 
a
nd bringing that home. They were frozen by the way And by the time they were thawed out, if you were lucky you had a few bodies, but if you were unlucky you had mostly heads. But still - it all made for taste, and that was a real delicacy with - the potat
oes that were more or less our staple food. But that was in the black days of the war.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember your mother having less food than the rest of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, I don't think because we wouldn't allow it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you allowed to talk during the meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. Oh yes, there were - out house - was a house of very little restrictions. Everybody - was allowed his point of view, and - if - the - you were - we were taught - that we were to allow even the younger ones to express themselves and say nothing.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 We always had to eat what was put before us, it was - there was no second choice at all, you either ate it - or you had to go without it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
They would ask the cause because - it wasn't often that - any would be, but - the only reason for something to be left over, was that you had ate something befo
re, which gave us away very often if we had been stealing apples, we wouldn't have place for our food and then - that would be or else we were sickening for something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your father have more food than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. My mother would graduate i
t out - for my father and the workers. My father and myself, the eldest and - and the younger ones would not need so much, that was the philosophy of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How would she serve the food out, would she serve it out on the plates or would you have it on the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
We would have the table - we - very very often if we were all together round the table, the potatoes would come straight from the saucepan and it would go right the way round, and then - soup - was very often that would come again from - anoth
er big container, it may be - and it was - doled out with a cup, a cup or a mug and there you are, and it was usually soup plates and you had everything, the meat - and the vegetables, and the soup swimming all and that was it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 In what order would you be served, who would your mother serve first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh it was all - everybody would be served together, nobody would dare start until - somebody - had asked grace. And I can always remember that grace and - it is even now - even now we do on a Sunday, we
 ask the grace. But this was the grace that was - asked at the time. May the Lord bless what his bounty has provided, for Jesus' sake, amen. But these little twins, it would come sometimes their turn to say grace, and they were so anxious to get at their 
food, so - one of them could do - just say, bounty, bounty, up and away then amen, and then dig into her food. That's quite true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who said the grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 We had to say it in turns. And - we did have Welsh - Welsh grace and English - we were taught th
e English in school of course but that was the - the one - that was the - usual. But we all had to say it in turn, parents included.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you all sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. We wou
ld all fit into the same place - my father at the end and my mother would just come in after everybody - she was the last to sit down and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where would she sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not very far from my father. Father at the head of the table, and - the
re was a big - as you would want for a family of ten, it was a big square table more or less - filled a big part of the room and we - would just sit around that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You can't remember how you sat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 My father at the table and my mother next - one end
 of the table next to the fire, and then - I would be - and my brother next to me - but the girls in order of - the eldest would be near my mother and we're coming back and - but therefore to help the younger ones where - where help was needed, it - it ju
st fitted into a pattern.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did they manage before they could feed themselves, the little ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
They had - what we call the - the high chair with the - platform in front of it. And there you are, they were - when the twins we had two of them, and one would be by my mother and the other would be by my eldest sister or - anybody else that would help -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So they'd be around the table with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, always around the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If there was something on the table that you wanted, like 
the salt, could you ask someone to pass it to you, or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh no, we would - it wasn't very often - I don't remember - very much, we - we weren't allowed to be very fussy. The salt was on the table if boil
ed eggs was on the menu, and naturally everybody would help himself to that. But I don't remember we were encouraged to add - pepper or salt, ever, my mother used to do that and you take it - just took it as it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. AND - you were welcome to it as long as it lasted. And then - you would hear - or else you'd hear somebody else scraping the bottom of a saucepan or something and - but there was not much left - after any - every meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way, or sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. We were - we were taught that I believe in school, in the infants - school, how you
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about taking a toy or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. It was - going to the table was a job of work. That was to - get it over as quick as possible, and to get away out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 There wasn't much restriction, if you were finished your food and there was something calling, well - you would just say,
 I'm off, and that was it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the lady who came to do the washing, did she eat with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, she did - and the lady that would come to - to - dressmaker. OH yes, they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they eat with you at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, same table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they have the same food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Exactly the same food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 They wouldn't have different food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Very. Very easy. The conversation would flow - from morning 'til night, it neve
r lagged and - the association of ideas, one thing would - suggest another, and - there was always something in the - in the mining - community, somebody always - was worse off than the others. And - as the poet said, about dwelling in the midst of alarms
, well that's what the environment of a mining village was. Somebody would be injured, and very often it would be a fatal accident. There would be somebody who had a new b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 by, and there would be a - somebody who had won a scholarship, there was no lack of variety in the conversation, and everybody would be interested in that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your mother show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
If necessary. Not - not so very - well I - we boys, at least, saying for myself - we resented it. We resented it very early, it was - considered girlish - to be a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 issy to be - we lived very near - we often had - bad - cuts and bruises which we never reported - to our parents and they would only see it when we were bathing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If you had any worries could you share them with your mother or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, it wasn't safe very often, our worries, the - the only worries that we did have was - our school teachers and schoolmasters, and we dare not say - tell them that we'd had a - the caning in school, because we'd have an extra one - for doi
ng it, so - we didn't take our troubles, we - just kept those to ourselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about your father, was he an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, he was very easy and he - you could discuss anything with him, and he had a keen - a very keen sense of h
umour. And would take us boys and the girls summertime he would go up the river. There was one pool in - Avon Valley, higher}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
up than the village, Robin Pool, which has an historical - background to it, but that pool was always - very deep - and - an ideal 
place, so he - took us there, well - before were six years of age, and literally threw us in and came in with us, and taught us to swim even then - would - carry us on his back and all of us and then he would dive down under you and leave you on the top b
ut - there you are, he saw to it that we - could fend for ourselves - very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did he show you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, I can't remember - any - any incident of affection - between my father and I. There was a resolve - he being a colliery manager - and
 I being a workman, I never wanted to be considered - the manager's son, I wanted to be on the same footing as my mates, and - that may be the reason for my resentment toward - any kind of side or affection or anything else - just call a spade a spade and
 - I want the same treatment for my work as my fellow men did from the work, and my father to me outside the house was just the manager.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well, looking back at it I had so many - outside - things between - the farm and the hors
es, and every - sport that would come, football came in, I was the captain of the - schools team, in the school, that's when the junior le}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 gue was formed in Port Talbot - and that was pre-1914. So between everything I only went home to roost as it were and to eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If you had any worries could you share them with your father or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Maybe I could if I - I knew - I knew if you had financial-and we - if you had financial - worries - well it was no good asking because it was not there. And that by th
e way was one of the - things I never forgave my parents, the school had half holiday because the circus had come to Port Talbot. All my friends - who had their sixpences to go, but I was refused the sixpence. By today I know - that it wasn't available. B
ut I was the one that walked down to Port Talbot and was outside the big top without having a sixpence to go in. And I - nursed that grudge against my mother for a long time until I came to know better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
You were expected to be - if they were asked you were to be o - you were to obey, obedience was demanded. And - you were expected as far as it was possible - to fend for yourself. Therefore the - carrying of - messages, and the helping of - w
ith the grocer, and when the - carrier used to deliver coal and coke to the school - to - get a few coppers for helping him, all that was - encouraged. But I don't think it was - it was no use going to ask for any financial favours like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes. Bullying - bullying was - it wasn't allowed at all. It wasn't allowed - my father had a way with that if he - started bullying, he would just - nip it in the b
ud and - there you forget it. It would be just one sharp tap and - he would say, now - there you knew it was time to break it off, it was - bullying was not allowed, and - you were to be obedient, and there was a family code that you were expected to live
 up to, and if you didn't well you suffered for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 My father - I was in many a fight as a boy. And - I think my father - he never discouraged me to defend myself. But he would - 
he would chastise you if - if you - took advantage of somebody smaller - or weaker than yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well the - I don't think - they were - over ambitious - our family wer
e not over ambitious, because we could see - in - other members of the families, such as cousins, removed, we could see that this over ambitiousness for their children led to - many - dissentions among the family. So I believe my parents were wise enough 
to let us - well - just go on in your own sweet way, if you've got anything in you it will come out, and if you haven't got it in you it's no good pushing empty barrels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. The importance - the greatest importance were - to be whatever work you undertook to be efficient in that work. If it was cutting coal well - be a good collier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It wasn't allowed, swearing was taboo. I - if you felt inclined like swearing you had to go - far enough away from our - from the house.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, we weren't. And - my mother had a way of saying - if - a younger ones would be too ken to li
sten to a conversation between my mother and a neighbour or between something else, she would just say in her way, that little pig's had very big ears, and we understood what that remark meant, and we made ourselves scarce.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well crime was graded at that time, if it was - something - ne}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 
ver were theft at that time, th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 eft, we were told - we were taught - the - commandment regarding - other peoples property, that never occurred but if it did, if it did you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 chastised}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 , and forcibly for that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 In what way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 There was always the remainder of the - birch stick on the mantle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ece. That was the birch rod.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they use it on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, they would use it - in certain cases they would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What would you have to do to have it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well - being told once to - not to play ball in a certain place, and persist in doing it and break some neighbour's window - well then that would deserve a birch rod.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would give it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Either - either my mother or my father. And they would have that and you'd have to run the gauntlet of that - of that stick while you could gallop up the stairs and get out of the way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How often would you be punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not very often. Not very often, the - well we had come to - to know that - delinquency and crime did not pay in our house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Can you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, I can remember that - occasion quite well and I deserved all I got then, I had three - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 chastisement}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 for that one deed. Outside the school, in Pontrhydyfen they were building new houses, and at that time they - for the - lime that they were using for ce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 lings and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 plastering}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717  - they used to excavate - ten 
square yards from a field - a yard deep and there they would have - tons of - lime, in that - hole, and add the water, until all that was a milky surface, right away. And that was a charm for the children of course. And they - we were all looking at this 
-
 and then it was burbling when it was warm. By the following day it would have settled, into an even custard all over. There we all looking at that - and the temptation was too much for me with the boy next to me, he was more or less hanging over the - an
d
 I helped him, with just a little push. And he couldn't bring himself back to balance and he stepped in up to his knees, in this putty lime. Well he was a - we had to help him out, but I had run away by this time. Well when I came back to school - the boy
s father had come, so that the headmaster dealt with me. And on the way home he called o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16523642\charrsid6557717 n my parents. And - I was dealt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 with there.. Put it off a minute.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you feel about being punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If I deserved it - if I deserved it well - that was a
ll right. I reconciled myself to that fact. And - but very often - very often having had the name of - in our - had a - a name for being - a bad boy, I had and was punished for many things afterwards that I did not do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
I resented that very very much. And I can always remember - some girl - who had made a complaint to the headmaster - and - I was absolutely - innocent of that - I wasn't punished for that but I still resented it, and - when I told them at home my father
 and my mother they were the first to go and to get that squared out and it was proved that I wasn't - they would uphold you in that but - that was - a very serious thing it was - it was she accused me of - theft, and theft of a coin which - I would never
 have done. Especially - well anyway - the coin was - it was discovered afterwards but far enough away from me. But otherwise I've have - my desserts and I've got away with quite a lot that I wasn't caught.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But your father and mother backed you up then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. They would, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 My mother played the greatest part in - in the influences. I rem
ember - when I was coming - fifteen, sixteen - where the time that we started looking at girls. And my mother taking me aside - and - telling me very very pointedly - that I had five sisters. And that I wasn't to treat any other girl - other than I would 
-
 treat my sisters. Which was a lesson I never forgot. But with my father, no, he knew - as a colliery manager he knew what was going on and the influences - in the colliery - were very very - they were influences for - bad, because - the element - of the 
Port Talbot and the Samfills boys that were working in the colliery - and the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 haulers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
 with their coarse languages - and all those things couldn't but - rub off on - on boys. But - my father was conscious that we - that I wasn't so innocent as that, he kne
w - that I was in this - but I never gave him to - occasion to believe that I was - one of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. Not - not the period of our childhood. The - birthdays were not - when you are
 - eight children - or ten in a family, they occur to often - to be made much fuss of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you have any presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The only present time was Christmas time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you have anything special to eat on your birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. I can't remember having celebrated any birthday - at a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well Christmas Day was very mixed, we had a service, there was a service in the chapel we - which we were expec
ted to attend in the morning. During my - when I was a lad I always used to play football, and Christmas morning we used to have the - derby days - playing one village against another. And - there you are, back home for the Christmas dinner, and invariabl
e
 a - an oratorio was performed on Christmas night, or a celebrity concert. That was the pattern of our Christmas. Now one of those Christmases stand out very very clearly, and it - I'm very glad all this experience by today, although it took me many years
 
to live it down. There was a derby day, football match between Cwmowan and Pontrhydyfen. I was a lad then of sixteen and a half, but - when you think that I started work at seventeen I was that one year - started work at thirteen I was that one year ahead
.
 So that I was seventeen and a half. And a big strapping lad playing forward So after the match my mother - but before I went - my mother had told me, now you remember are back for dinner, and don't you go - and be tempted to drink anything down there tod
a
y, don't spoil the dinner for us son and for you. So - after the match - and we had won these boys were saying, come on, have a drink. Have a pint. I said, no. There's no pint today, I don't want to spoil my dinner. Oh very well. But one of the boys had t
h
e bright idea - oh - try this. And he came along - with a small little glass, a short Oh that was very very nice. And I asked, well what is this? Rum and peppermint, he said. Well being we were ten in the company, it went around of rum and peppermint, and
 
that's the Christmas I didn't see at all. Somehow or other - I got home, and to bed, without dinner. But for the next three days - if I would have tea or a glass of water - the rum would come up. But it taught me this one thing. It gave me - a - well I - 
abhor - liquor ever since, and that Christmas taught me that lesson, and kept me off spirits.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, my father had a violin. A violin, he was a keen violinist, been trained - by - a Mr Moodie, that
 was - he was a music master in Neath. He -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You mentioned earlier about him being with Doctor David Evans?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. Ah but - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Just your father played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did anybody else play anything in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, not at that period, we did - later on - graduate to a piano. And then a few of them came to play the piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When was that, after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. My brother who was younger than me, he was a - an 
eminent boy soprano. Much sought after during the war to sing in smokers that were held for the - soldiers coming home. And it was at that period - that a harp came to the village. And - with the harp came - penillion singing. And - that was an occasion. 
S
o that - Samuel Davis, he - taught himself to play the harp, my father had a good tenor voice and with his violin, but - singing with a harp came - for the first time to the locality. Well my brother, he was a - had been trained, and there was a competiti
on in the national eistedfood at Barry, for singing - twelve to fifteen, singing with the harp. Penillion singing. And Elwyn my brother won the prize - for singing the harp - winging with the harp in Barry. Was that 1920? Somewhere about 1920 that was.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, that was - as soon as the programme would come out - we would be well versed in the programme.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You mean the Gymanfa ganu?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The gymanfa ganu programme, yes. And - with the family I have
 mentioned, the Griffiths's that were a few doors - they - were more musical than we were. And had an harmonium. And they - and they still are today, if you will sing a tune, a hymn tune, they'll tell you the name of it. Or you ask the name of a humn tune
 and one of the Griffiths's will sing it for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you make music with them when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes. Especially when we would come - carol singing. The two families would unite, and we would go out - and we'd sing - outside the doors through Oakwood, just for the sheer enjoyment of it, the two families singing Christmas carols.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The only game that I ever remember in our house was draughts. And - later dominoes. But - not with my paren
ts. Later - when the - memorial hall was instituted, that was after the war - there was an old man in the place who was a keen chess player, and he taught - a generation of us - the art of chess playing. And once you have mastered chess - draughts and dom
inoes you forget all about those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Plenty - plenty of books. Polenty of books. The - the books - were - everywhere, Cymru - cyrru goch, cyrmru - cenhadwr - cymr cogh, cwmru plant. And as those books came out - my
 father would have them and would give them to us - and all those books, we were well acquainted with those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about newspapers, you mentioned that your father had the golaued?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And the Faner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The Faner. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And the Cymro?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh the Cymro I don't think was out at that time. No it wasn't, it wasn't no, no, the Faner it was then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about any other newspapers would you have then when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 My mother would have Home Notes. My father would have ama
teur Gardening. And there was this Science and Art of Mining which you could always turn to. But the one thing that revolutionized our - our reading habits - my uncle - Uncle Morgan who had come from the university in Aberystwyth having graduated had taug
ht for just a - a twelve month, and was called to the war in 1914. He was a L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
eutenant that was - wounded in Murmetz Wood, and came back to Swansea, to Sketty in Swansea convalescent, and - he - was giving - presents of books, and I can always remember them, he gave us the Children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 s Tennison, the children Shakespeare, the children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 s Dickens and those were so absorbing that we swallowed those. Afterwards I graduated to when I had my own coppers - from school to buy Nelson Lee, the detective - story, and Sext
on Blake. So that I was well versed in - in those again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember your mother reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, I do. My mother used to read - the Home Notes - Home Notes were the - with my mother. And she would have - a periodical - the - Kenadur. She was a
 very very - she was very keen - on foreign mission work, and all - literature that would come from that direction - my mother, that was her life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember your father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. And - Emerson - my father - was - he could be called 
to - speak on practically any subject, and he was so versatile that he could - I remember many saying, I didn't - remember so much of - of that, but I remembered others saying that he - he - was so well read, so versatile, that he could speak on any subje
ct.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other? You did tell me that your father used to read aloud to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 R.S. Jones, Upper Brighton, I just mentioned that, and if there was anything that would - interest my father, or my mother, they wou
ld transfer it to us, it was shared.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they read aloud to each other, your father and mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Only - snatches. Snatches of this - one would ask - especially - what do you think of this, and - there he would read it. And then again - my mother would have found something in her reading that - she would transfer it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, I can remember - there was one - one tragedy in our - life, between the - twins - and Rhoda, there was a - a little baby, Ei
rian, Eirian, and - he died in infancy, about six months old. And I can remember that - small little coffin, and the gloom that descended upon the household. That is my first recollection - of it, in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You'd only be about five or six, you don't remember the funeral or what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Not so much as - well I can remember them - leaving the house. What I can remember is this little coffin, and it was painted white with blue - it wasn't the brown - oak - that is very vivid in my mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You don't remember who attended the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Outside our family - I cannot say - so much about - about that, only the effect. The first contact - with death.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you have to wear mou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Not taken out to visit the - colliers home at that time was an open - open place for every - people came and went all day long and every day. Invariably somebody or other would turn 
in - at any time of the day, and night, and especially the - winter nights, where they would come in - to have a - tune on the - to learn the hymn tunes from the programme or anything and later after the harp came to the place, the - harp singing, that be
came the craze, but - as far as our house was concerned, there was always somebody there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would be there, would they be friends or neighbours or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well our family - we were a very very large family, which were called - the wythien f
awr, the big vein, and that - went - the tentacles of the Thomases from - that village were everyw}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
ere. So there were such a large family - one of the other would come in, and if we felt like visiting anybody, and even now after all the years - there's har
dly a house in the village that I can't go and just walk in without even knocking. Just a salutation, anybody at home? And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 People would come in without knocking would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Wouldn't knock at all, there's - just - they would give the tap and op
en the come in, and just ask, in Welsh, any people here? And then the - they would break the news if it was news or they would ask the question if they wanted to know for if they wanted to borrow something, somebody had run out of tea or sugar or soap or 
something, practically every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you be taken shopping when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No. We weren't going - the - it wasn't a very big village altogether, and - after the Co-operative was instituted it was the Co-operative, and the - there t
he - we would be taken over and - with a long list of the order for the week. And then even back in those days there was a - a delivery by horse and cart. And if not - we would just carry - carry on - one or two journeys and bring what we wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you go as a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, as - I was the eldest and quite a lot of that, the heavy work - fell on me from - when I was very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you go on your own or would somebody be with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, it's - usually on your own, the - you'd pic
k up with somebody if you wanted help you could always call on - your friends and he would only be too willing to oblige.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. Very seldom, unless he - we - he would take us, he was a - a keen fisherman.
 And if there were - holiday, such as Bank Holiday, I can remember going with him - fishing. But - it was too tedious of a job for me when he - but he used to - make his own flies, and one comes very very - vivid back to my mind now. While we'll be killin
g the cockerel he would choose a few feathers from his neck to make this fly, coch y boncyff, coch yboncyff, which I think is still a well known fly for trout fishermen. Those were the only - outings that we would go with our father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you all go on Bank Holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No. He would only take the - he would take the three eldest. Well then there were the - there were so many - attractions for the young ones and - what we - boys, the two boys - didn't want - was the company of our - sisters We didn't
 want to be seen with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
There was something then - the old petticoat, that's the - and it - that was the worst thing they could call you, to call you a - call a little boy an old petticoat - was the worst - thing of all, so you wanted to avoid that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, your sister mentioned the trip to Aberavon beach with Mrs Griffiths.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, those were annual - summertime trips. The train was very convenient and it would take us down t
o Aberavon, or sometime to the - the beach although there was - a mile of a walk from this - from Swansea Bay, Aberavon beach stati}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 n down to the beach actually. Those were days when we used to take the kettle and - take all our food, and - over to the dun
es and it would be for a day, back and for into the sea, and - those were the kind - we would have those - about twice in the summer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The - there would be three or four families would be - coming then and the mothers would - 
and the strongest of the boys in the families would be carrying these - kettle, it would be a big iron kettle at that time, and another one would be taking some - sticks, that - to light the fire. And of course the - something to - teapot and a few mugs t
o drink the tea out of and - it was a big outing at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No. I don't think I slept from home - only once, only once I can remember and that ended in tragedy and disaster. We had been taken over to our gra
ndmother. My brother and I - and - the tale had gone on long - so - we had gone to sleep while the elders were talking. My grandmother said, oh put those two in - in the bed there, and they left us there. We woke sometime, it was dark, found ourselves in 
a strange place and started bawling - and in the end my uncle had to take us in the middle of the night back home, and that was the only time - that I can ever remember sleeping away from home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And where was your grandmother's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh she was only a
cross the river. In Pontrhydefen - the Pontrhydyfen part was - under the estate, Lord Jersey Estate, and the - across the bridge was Oakwood, which was the Margam Estate, so that is only just across the river that - separated us. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did any of the other members of the family go on holiday at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not that - not while we were children. It was a long time - long time before we came to - to the holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you go at all before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about Saturdays in those days, how would you spend Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Saturday, there were - in the place there was another - grocer - who had - opened out on his own. And there was always a chance on a Saturday, to earn a shilling, and it was a long - it was from Friday evening - 'til about
 five o'clock on Saturday, and - especially during the wintertime, people would order a bag of potatoes. And that - would have to be taken on a hand truck. And - a strong youngster - would be able to deliver the sack of potatoes, and - two or three orders
 the furthest away - these orders in the big box and - for that type of thing we could earn these - shillings, which I think were a help even I - I wasn't allowed to have it all for myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did you do with the money you earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I must admit 
to this, that - smoking - came - early in my life. When I was in standard three really, because it was - standard three of the school, there wasn't enough place in the school, so that we were in the vestry of a chapel, about two hundred yards away from th
e
 school, with plenty of chance for boys to smoke, and - to begin with we were helping ourselves to the shag that our fathers smoked. But then we graduated on to Woodbine, which were - at that time one penny for five. And the lady that was selling them wou
ld give us two - for a ha'penny, the first time, and you'd have three for the ha'penny the next time and she never made a mistake. So - that - smoking Woodbine - that was - and of course - those took our coppers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How old would you have been in standard three?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Eight. Looking back at - eight years of age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You were never caught?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, caught and - but it wasn't considered - it wasn't considered a crime then to smoke - and anyway the - schoolteachers - sent us very very often to - to buy th
e cigarettes. And when we would fail to get tobacco of any kind we would resort to baco dail, leaf tobacco, and baco dail we used to have - the herb - foxglove leaves. I don't know exactly what those - what that is, it's a type - very much like the chrysa
n
themum leaf, but the bottom of that plant, the leaves would be dying and drying, and we would - dry those a bit more and rub them that we could make a cigarette - and - we smoked many of those when we failed to have tobacco, but I can always remember goin
g into - a - a - a patient who suffered from asthma who was burning Potters Asthma Cure, and that was the same - exactly the same aroma was from Potters Asthma Cure as we used to get from the - baco dail as we called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It probably didn't do you any harm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you work all day on Saturday at that little job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, it would be - up until - about four or five o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And you said Friday night as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, you start - if there were - we would just call or the grocer wo
uld have called in the house and said that there was - that he would like to do such and such thing on Friday night, and - therefore we would do just those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How old would you be when you started to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I was - I'm sure I was delivering for 
the - at the age of ten. But here's another - another sideline that we had. The - Echo was the only evening paper in the village, that was coming down - coming by train, and - there used to be a sale of about five to six dozen - of the - of the Echo. Well
,
 when somebody was wanted - new - a newspaper boy, Echo boy, the - man from Cardiff used to come to the school, and - having been recommended by the headmaster or the teacher for a likely boy, and then he would go and - ask our parents. So - I came to be 
- the representative of the Echo selling the Echoes. And I must - I did that for a few years. That -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How old would you have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Ten. Well now, this is how I know so - that I was an Echo boy at ten. I can remember going to the station one 
night to fetch my papers, and - I was very surprised when the parcel for Pontrhydyfen came out - with twice if not three times the amount of papers that I usually had. Well I - took them with me, but to my surprise, before I could go very far from the sta
t
ion, half the village came to meet me, and all asking for a paper. And as - as I was giving them out, and they were - a penny I believe if it was penny or ha'penny the Echo was at that time, and that was the night of the explosion at Senghenydd. '13, you 
see. And I was born 1903, so that would put - so that's the - we used to have I think - tuppence a dozen, I think it was tuppence a dozen was the - the sale for the - for selling papers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How often would you do that, every evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 That was every night. 'Til Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the money you had from that, would you give any of it to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh my mother did all of that, the - there were many bad debts - but sometimes when the fireworks were around there 
would be an occasional penny missing. But - taking all the - money that I received - for the papers, they paid weekly mostly, giving it to my mother, and she used to - send it away to Cardiff, and - I don't remember - having received anything - well to sa
y that I was having it for that, because - all going to the kitty, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You don't know what she'd spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Those little incidentals that - that crop up - such as - there were quite a lot of - small - penny readings and eistedfodds. And an occ
asional c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
ntata or something in other chapels apart from us, with an entrance fee of a penny or tuppence. And when they - those coppers were coming very useful - for that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the little job you had with the grocer, how much of that would you give to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well of that shilling - more than likely - maybe I would keep it one week and perhaps it was expected of me to give it the other week.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you know what that was spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well Woodbine would be coming 
into it. And the only other would be - a contribution towards - buying a ball. A football, or a - whatever was sport was in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you get on with the grocer? And the other boys you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh there was - there was not much dissention but
 luckily I was endowed with a strong body, I was an aggressive youngster, and for that I was respected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did your employer treat you, the grocer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh very very good. They - all through the years there was - somebody who'd say have a big order 
and - he - the lady might say, oh I'd like to get these over tonight. Oh all right, he said, I'll see that you get it. And when the word would come, whatever else had to go by, I would deliver those goods as wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you like the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, I
 did because it was always a change. It was always a change of going from Oakwood to Pontrhydyfen, from Pontrhydyfen to Twyn y Pandy and then to - Cerrig Llwydon and then to Efail Fach. And - being the village was only a mile altogether but you had those 
distinctions between the lot. And every one that lived there were different from the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Why do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Now the - the difference I think came, Oakwood people - Oakwood being the newest - buildings, the new buildings were in Oakwood. So the
y would be the ones that were in the new houses, considered themselves or - were thought to be - just that little bit - higher than the ones that were in the old cottages of Pontrhydyfen and - then Twyn y Pandy again there were - that was a new - built - 
n
ew houses there, but in Cerrig Llwydon, as the name suggests and Efail Fach were the old part. But there was this difference also. It was in Oakwood, the church, the Church of England then was. And the church - the people that went to the Church of Englan
d - usually had - they were English or had English connections. Therefore we in Pontrhydyfen mostly - were the Calv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
nistic Methodists, who had come down from Gyfylchi, that started in 1777, so we were there first established, and over in - Cerrig Llywdon an
d Efail Fach, that's where you had Gwyr Sardis who were the independent of the Congregationalist as we know them today, so there were those distinctions in the village then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You think in different parts of the village, people of the different denomin
ations lived really in different parts? Do mean that the church people sort of tended to live in Oakwood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well they found themselves in Oakwood - mostly. The - the colliery officials for instance - they were living - they could afford the newer house
s. They came there. And then there were the business people. They more or less - went to the new houses that were built - that were built in Oakwood. And left the old - or came from other - parts of the - of Wales or the country, came to that part.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you feel because you were Calv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 nist Methodist in Oakwood, did the people all mix with each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, you couldn't - there - there wasn't a distinct line of demarcation but - it was - now a ni, they and us. That was - evident.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The church was English of course,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The church was English, yes, yes, that - in my time. And all the other - chapels were Welsh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You mentioned that the business people went to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Publicans. Church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would you say went to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
All the chapel people were - they came the family - the old families - first of all there were the families of - the farmers who instituted Gyfylchi back in 1777, and then their offspring - as I say there were families, they - you - you could - say 
six to ten families, and they and their offspring, they were the ones that formed - Gyfylchi went too small of a place in - by 1826, and that's where Jerusalem, Pontrhydyfen was built. And that of course was the biggest one. I can't remember what exactly 
happened that the - the Baptist of course, they had - although the Baptist chapel was in Oakwood, and the Independ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
nts was in Efail Fach. I can't say myself when those divisions started, but - it always has been and it is today, that the Calv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
nistic Methodist - were the strongest in the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And it was the farmers you think really were the chapel people in the beginning, people used to walk for miles didn't they?
