\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh Sundays was a day of - we - it was completely 
devoted to the chapel. There was a service at half past nine, from half past nine to half past ten. The service for - the young - members-. And - that's where they were taught to take part. And I can remember a few of them, one for instance was the Revere
n
d Emlyn Jones, in Johannesburg now, became an eminent preacher - but I can remember him in these meetings at half past nine - taking part, so we were graduated quietly to - give one - stanza of a hymn, and then we would be asked to read a few verses, and 
t
hen after quite a long time we may be asked to give the benediction, and it was in that way that young people - were - introduced to the work of the church. That was half past nine 'til about quarter past ten, we would just go outside and - but the mornin
g service would start at half past ten. Usually a sermon by the minister or some other}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
minister. Two o'clock Sunday school, and we dare not lose Sunday school. The - different teachers from the vestry and you went from there into the chapel, and I can remem
ber one class - a class of mothers, and that - that time there may be a dozen women there with babies in shawls, in that corner. And - my mother, as soon as she could she wouldn't lose the Sunday school. We would all be in Sunday school. Back to a very qu
i
ck tea because the Band of Hope would be at five, and - to the Band of Hope. Then the - evening service at six, and invariably there would be a Ysgol gan after that - during the - period when we were - training for the gymanfa ganus at Easter, And the gym
anfa bwnc, which was on Good Friday, so there was not much time in the Sunday.
