Oh no. No, Sunday was - we weren't allowed to do anything. My - this was the experience - that I will always remember. I have just mentioned that I could earn a few}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 
 coppers, and I can remember buy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ing and old boneshaker of a bike for five shilli
ngs, I had saved five shillings to buy that. But it was going - and - in school it was before I was twelve, in school then - one of our mates had had appendicitis, the first time we had ever heard the name, the only hospital to treat it at that time was S
w
ansea General Hospital, before Aberavon or any other hospital in Neath - everybody had to go to Swansea. Well we were four of his mates wanted to go to Swansea - visiting him on a Sunday. And the only way to get to Swansea on a Sunday was - either walk or
 
go on a bike, there were no trains, there was nothing. Before the days of cars. Well I remember coaxing my parents for a week, for permission to ride that bike on a Sunday. It wasn't done, you dare not take that outside, and if you defied - you - couldn't
 
be surprised if you found that somebody had - damaged that for you and they would put it out of order that you wouldn't go. But I did have permission to go with my friends, on condition that I was in the half past nine meeting, that I was in the half past
 ten meeting, I was allowed to lose Sunday school for the time but I was to be back by six o'clock. So that was - how things were - as far as sport and - any kind of - activity on the Sunday.
