s
. They weren't thought much of at that time, because - we all had school were brainwashed with the land of hope and glory and the patriotism and everything, and - this is just the type of thing we were taught at school. We are all under the same old flag,
 
Britain's in arms are we, one King and one desire, one flag and one empire, England, Scotland, Ireland, Wales, dominions o'er the sea. We'll fight with might because it's right to conquer Germany. That was the type of - in school. And our headmaster at th
a
t time - was - officers training corps and there they were with broom sticks until they had rifles marching up and down the village, as - an officer - OTC officers training corps - during the first world war. There were a few who - were conscientious obje
c
tors, and they who had to suffer. Well after the war they came back, and by that time I had been working in the underground and was a - a - full grown man who had my own pay and my pocket money, and a few more beside. But this - man who was a schoolteache
r
 he brought us together, and - formed a little class, and it was he that introduces us to a literature that was different from what we had in the chapel. And - the thin edge of the wedge of - he being an ILP he brought in political science. And very soon 
I
 had - graduated - to become a trade unionist very young, and - went from there to the committee of the - the works committee in the colliery, and this is important in my life, I was chosen as a delegate, to go to the - annual conference, three day confer
e
nce at Corry Hall in Cardiff, where representatives of all the lodges - of the coalfield gathered. I was representing the Argoed colliery - as their delegate. And those were the strong words at that time. I - you had Tom Richards in the chair, Vernon Arms
t
rong immaculately dressed. You had Sir William Jenkins - Beattie, and quite a lot more, and once I found myself sitting next to a young man - and - conference was - interrupted - by - a request that the conference should hear a deputation from nine mile p
o
int, those miners been on strike - had walked from Nine Mile Point to Cardiff. And - some were saying, oh we can't be bothered because Nine Mile Point, there's always some row or - strike there. But this young man next to me, he got up on his feet, and - 
a
nd - and start - started to stut - stut - stutter, but - once he got over that first stutter he spoke very forcibly, and - Nine Mile Point deputation was - granted an audience by the conference. And I found later that that young man was none other than - 
Aneurin Bevan. So - those - the activities - when I was young, that was when I was seventeen 'til - until we went down to Kenfig Hill I was in the Labour movement, and - would be put by this - Aneda Rees it was, put by him - to ask questions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What happened to those conscientious objectors who were in the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Those conscientious objectors they - they had a very - tough time of it, they were put in solitary confinement, and - then they would be - offered - a - they would be taken out for a bath, w
hich would be nothing but - cold water. Their clothes would be taken away from them, and they would be - offered a suit of khaki, and kept there sometimes - all day - and either they took the khaki or else they would - and a lot of them died young, the ef
f
ects of the one of them in particular I know - who after he came back - had lost his health, but he moved to North Wales, and - couldn't have known then that - he - I - he wasn't - he wouldn't have been - wouldn't have stood a chance of having the teachin
g position in - South Wales.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Why wouldn't he have had a chance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Because - the Glamorgan County Council and the ones that were - fitting them in - patriotism had not altogether died, and - there were teachers that were coming back - from the - de
mobilized from the army, and they would be fitted first. But a strange coincidence - three years ago my son-in-law was appointed a headmaster - of a school at Berwyn in the Bala, and one of the first things he did - was to look at the school log book, and
 he came home and he said that he was so very surprised, a boy from Pontrhydyfen - has been a headmaster in this school. But he died a young man. And that was - the late Jenkin William James, of Pontrhydyfen, and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  he was one of these - conscient}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ious objectors that - from the first world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What was the feeling in the village when they were conscientious objectors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Now again you will find where the feeling of the village - was - evident - in - the church, the Anglican church. The Anglican church e
n bloc were - ultra-patriotic, the King the Queen and the - there you are, you're - looking back at it you can see that, and they were the ones - that would pin the white}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 feather to any boy, who they thought was - should have been -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they do that in Pontrhydefen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
They would, oh yes. I can remember one of them - during - Major Jack Edward's recruiting officers were coming - and - somebody was brave enough to get up in the meeting to speak against this recruitment. And this woman who was - she w
as a church woman, and I can hear her saying now, chuck him out, and - it was not - no opposition was tolerated against the establishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was there a choir in the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. There was a choir and I should have said that one more branch of the
 Sunday school and the Band of Hope, was - John Curwn's modulator had come out, and - we had a - a class of solfar, and that was an hilarious - experience to be there with Thomas Griffiths. We would run up and down the scale, and - became very very effici
ent - efficient in - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 solfa, and I am very indeb}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
ted to it, I - use it even today. Never having learnt the staff, but one meeting the - teacher would be with his pointer going up and down and we were - we were supposed - to - sing after him, or he'd put o
n the blackboard - a series of notes, and we were to - sing them. But one of the boys, he just had a look at the blackboard, and - on his feet, but this is just what he said. Me doh, ray do, so fa, so fa ray doh me. And that ended the class for that night
 
in laughter, we could never - instead of singing it he just said it. Now those kind of things. Afterwards we had - a glee party, under Thomas Griffiths, and that glee party - well for the first time, we - learnt something that was - different, for the - s
u
ch as - the Jolly Roger Boys. That was something new. Of course we had the old - Mevanwy, and - quite a lot of the old ones. But then we - went on to something better. We had a madrigal choir. And these madrigals, when we had their history - revealed to u
s
 - and to know that they had survived - all those centuries, and what was different in the madrigal - to the other parts in the glee party, was that there would be four or even six - distinct parts, which were sung to everyone, and the strains of those ma
drigals, even today, repeat themselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did the chapel run a temperance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 club? You did mention a Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The Band of Hope yes, and there was a - I don't remember the Good - Good Templars as such - I don't remember my having - ever having si
gned the pledge. But the - boys that were just slightly older than myself, had done just that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you a member of the Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh the Band of Hope would - would sing the hymns from - Swn y Jiwbili, and
 Swn y Jivili was the - the Welsh equivalent to the - Sankey and Moodie. Singing songs we would sing them, Sow Seeds of gentleness, whereas the English ones would be singing - Sow gentle seeds of kindness. Well it was - it were those - and would train us 
- for the penny readings, which we - gave us the grounding of public speaking and - gave us the - breaking down the - shyness that we could appear on a stage - that was taught very - early, and that was from the - Band of Hope.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 That's why so many Welsh people are actors and preachers and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. There was plenty of facilities for you, you had it in - you had little tasks to do from the Sunday school, you had a chance to appear on your own in - in the Band of Hope. When the cantatas came a
long you were given a par and then later came - the drama, and when the dramas to be - chosen for a par for the drama - and - I was chosen for those too I remember doing the Portia, and had quite a lot of - I was Thomas Shaw in Geo Francis's Portia, and I
 can always remember the thrill of that, and then went on to do the \{BLANK\} and - many many more of these dramas, which gave confidence, which many today think is - audacity and cheek, but it was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Grace was said at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was it always said, and who would say it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. Grace was always said in our house at every meal. And one of the family had to say it. I can remember - the - allar deuluoedd, or the family altar, that was - carried on - without a break in my grandmother's house t
o the end, while she and my grandfather were. I remember it in our house, but on a Sunday night only. Where the family would congregate together, before we would go to rest on a Sunday night, and my father would read}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 a few verses and he would pray and he w
ould give the benediction and - commit us to God if you like, for the coming week. And I remember that. But it would be - up until - the first world war, 1914. Many things went by the board from that date.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes, he - my father was a Liberal, Liberal - to - an ardent Liberal, so much so that - when the - Mid-Glamorgan - elections took place, and S.T. Owens, the member, the committee rooms were 
in our front room. And the comings and goings at that time during election time - were an experience for young children at that time, and we would sneak into the - public meetings that were held in the school or in the chapel vestries and - well everythin
g - and we would - sing this - we children were taught. O give a loan of a penny to buy a red coffin to bury Vaughan Rehola in the middle of the pigs manure. Well, Liberals it was all the time, and Dad was a big man with Lloyd George and when the L}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 oyd Geor
ge insurance came Dad thought that that was something exceptionally good. And there is one interesting thing about Lloyd George insurance. When the thing sta}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ted Dad was working as a collier and then part of the contribution was being paid in the colliery 
and he paid a portion but after he became the manager of the works he was not eligible then. He was not to pay because he was considered above the insurance of a workman. But dad because he had been from the start he was able to pay as a voluntary contrib
utor and I can remember the commotion when the card was being collected in, every six months, and the club superintend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
nt coming to ask for the card and no stamp on it and mother having to gather as much money as she had in order to stamp the card but then 
the promise was made to stamp it every week from then on. But this is what happened years later. Dad had been paying voluntarily the stamp, well he died a young man and mother with five little ones in school and the widow's pension had come in and mother 
f
ills the form in to have the widow's pension now, and a long time before anybody answered the letter but one day here is a gentleman coming to the door. Mrs Edwards? She said Yes. I see you've applied for the widow's pension. And - I see that the occupati
on of your late husband was col}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
iery manager, do you know that he wasn't eligible to pay that insurance? Well, my - my mother said, well I have paid it. Well have you any evidence madam, the inspector? Yes, my mother. And she went to fetch these, a bundle o
f the cards that had been signed and filled in - through the years. And the gentleman looked at my mother and smiled and said, congratulation madam, you are a woman in five thousand. It is my painful duty so very often - when - I go to examine these cases
,
 to find out that somebody had given up maybe six months ago or just last years and would have forfeited their pension for that - neglect. But you madam, you are - case is straight forward, and that meant quite a lot to my mother, to have the widow's pens
ion - for herself and the five dependent children which made a big difference in the budget of our family at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You said he was a Liberal, your father, why do you think he held those views
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well he had - he had gone through being a - an or
phan, he had lost his father very - he never remembers his father, and - he was very very conscious of the - of the state that people, especially widows were living in. And - undoubtedly the - the effects of - the ILP had begin - had begun even at the tim
e, to seep in. Well anyway, he - he was the Liberal because - Liberal stood for radicalism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about your mother, did she take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Non-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 committal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
, my mother was one of those people - she had seen so much of it Because we - w
e lived in a place and she knew that - if people started to argue - about politics that that would soon go to some kind of quarrel and dissention so mam was peace at any cost, and wouldn't - she never expressed her views politically.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You don't know what her views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh she would follow her husband, she - she would - she - there is one thing certain about my mother, she would never vote Tory. Because we had seen the effect of - the landlords through the years. So - it is more than likely that 
it was a Liberal my mother was too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember your father and mother voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. Yes, I - I'm going back now - oh that was - I shouldn't be surprised that it about 1910 - the - candidate - Mr Vaughan R
heole, Mr Vaughan of Rheale estates, he was the Tory member, and - there was no place for him - in Pontrhydyfen at that time. So while - while the - Liberal flag was flying my father was all out for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 In some places at that time men felt they risked
 losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers, do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure, to vote for a particular party? Of course he was colliery manager wasn't he, and then he went back to be 
a collier, and then he went to be manager gain, how did he feel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
It didn't apply in the village of Pontrhydyfen so much - the people that were affected - were those who depended upon their landlord. Now in the village in Pen y Bryn where I live now - 
the farmers there - before every election, even for a parish or a council election - were honoured by a village - a visit from - the - agent of the estate, of the Margam Estate at that time, and were told in no uncertain terms that if it was known - that 
t
hey had voted for anybody - but the candidate that was specified - by their - the landowner, then they would be deprived of their - and there are a few - instances of people - having lost their farms. But - at that time I don't think that it applied to th
at degree - in - as far as coalminers were concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was your father a member of the political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, oh yes, an active member.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And you would remember him working for the Liberal party at an election? Was your mother a member?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, I don't think that they were - that women at that time - I can't - remember - any active woman - with the - political parties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 They didn't have the vote until after the war did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, there was nothing in the - nothing in the village - my father was - attached to the union, but they had the - the coal owners association - they had some functions - which their colliery managers were attending. Ap
art from that I don't think there was anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well it was - my mother - was - always - either knitting - most of us wore socks, stockings at that time. Stockings t
hat were - knitted. And I think that it was considered a - a mark of slovenliness on any woman who was not doing something in that respect. I can always remember there was - a stocking, or a glove - and later on there came little jerseys for the boys and 
-
 no, it was more or less the - things about the family in the weekdays There wasn't a tremendous lot by the time - the train was going up in the morning at six o'clock, and it wasn't coming back until four. By the time the meal was over and bath time - it
 
was very near time to go to a weeknight meeting or whatever - was going. And the free nights that there were, by the time you had - read the paper and the Goleuad and - whatever periodical - either - mum or my dad were reading - it was time to go to bed -
 being you were getting up early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Only chapel - matters. There was - nothing else to interest my mother, the chapel - and the - the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Apart from an occasional outing to see friends in - the neighbouring village of Cwmavon or - that was just about the limit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 With whom would she go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 She would go either with her sisters, or one of her sister-in-law's, or the immediate neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well really by the time you'd come in - when he was working in the Avon Valley, he was - the trains, the colliers trains that were coming from the - the far end of the Avon Valley, Blyngwnvy
 down to Port Talbot, it was a tremendous train of - fourteen, fifteen coaches. And - if you - if any collier lost the train well he either had to - walk, or wait for the next passenger train - and travel standing up - in the - guards van. But normally I 
would be home from - twenty to half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well, he would spend the evenings up until - the church meetings would start That was Monday prayer meeting, Thursday Society, and - I'm not quite sur
e how often the Bristol, West Of England, South Wales Provident he was - that he would be attending, that meeting was usually - was on a Friday night. But he wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would that be every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. Yes. He wasn't going very far from the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father attend any clubs or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh no. That wasn't the - that wasn't - there was no club - in the - in the village. And the effect of the 1904/5 revival - had not - absolutely brushed off. There was a distinct gap - between the - ones that w
ere too - fre - to frequent the public houses, and the ones that frequented the chapels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 There were people in Pontrhydyfen then who didn't go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, there were - there were people - there was a Conservative Club - that - was back in 
- but the revival - smothered that. And in the little hamlet of Tonmawr, up above, the - religious revival was sufficient - to close the only pub - that was up there, and - Tonmawr was dry, until very lately when the new craze of football clubs were insti
tuted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would your mother go at all for anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh no - my mother - as I've said, she was - a temperance movement that - and it was - with her - one of her deadliest enemy, and - I know for a fact that she would refuse even for medicin
al purpose - she would refuse to have any - alcohol, such as brandy or whisky in the house at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father take part in any sport?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The only sport I remember my father, I have just mentioned that he was a - a fisherman, but - there was -
 one more sport - didn't live very long. There came as a minister to the place - a young man who had been to Cambridge Later he became professor W.P. Jones of Trevicker. He came as a young minister to Pontrhydyfen, and he was the first to introduce the ga
me of quoits. And I can remember as a child - watching these grown up men throwing those iron rings, which we became to know as quoits. And - but that only lasted - as long as that minister was in the - in the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father ever attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No. Horse racing - had not started. It became later - but - very much after my father - but pony racing, pony racing started to come - the Neath races was only just outside Pontrhydyfen, but that again was - was not - thought the thing. And I may
 - mention by passing, that the nickname by which Pontrhydyfen people are known, and some refer to it now, as the money boxes. They had the name of being - very very thrifty, and kept their money in money boxes, but there is a reason for that too. My gran
d
father remembers the time - when a slick Englishman came to Pontrhydyfen and deprived these people of their savings, another one appeared afterwards, in my mother's time, and he - he again deprived - and later on, afterwards, there was a confidence tricks
ter came, so when people have been had three generations of them like that, the bookmaker hasn't got much chance with people like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How were they had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well - the first one came - and asked people to invest - in collieries. And - painted the r
osy picture. But - of course after having the shareholders in and so forth, somehow the mine came to an end and - the people would lose all. The other one afterwards - I'm not quite certain of the - of the second one - defrauded them, but I know that the 
third - the third - got these people to invest - in some unknown company - and he used to pay - used to pay the dividends pretty regularly. But when it came that the people wanted - to have the bulk of their own money, when the crash came it was final.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He didn't bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, the Bristol.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was that a savings club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, no, the Bristol West of England and South Wales was a provident society, only to the extent that you - it was called -
 club claf, it would only - it would only give you - those few shillings when you were unable to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It was a sick club really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Sick club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 He didn't belong to anything else like a boot club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 People used to pay a penny a week for burying didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh that was - as insurance, yes, they did, because - my grandfather was an insurance agent. And - he made all the family insurance minded. That every child there was - from a penny to three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 pence a week on them. And also there was - just sufficient to guarantee that the parish wouldn't have to bury them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So they did pay that for all the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters, before leaving school when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh I was always kingpin, and - the eldest and that used to be the order, that the - younger ones, they did rebel but - in the end it was - they would - condescend to go and do what they were told by their elders. It paid them to do that, in many
 respects, because they were the ones who came to ask elder ones - to help them mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, perhaps - or not - we didn't have - we didn't have a weakling in the family thank God. Invariably I knew m
y friends - who were attached to a member of the family, if he was, for some reason, a weakling or deformed. But I don't remember having - to be - tempted to - give any - preference to one over the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Your sister was saying that she felt the three oldest were together more in your family? You didn't feel that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, we didn't - the - the reason for the three eldest being - of course we were the - three - that remembered most - pre-1914. The others were - more or less - regimented by rationing, and the shortages of the war and all that came after it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well the village was - very - prolific - in - breeding children, and you never - were short of company. There were plenty to play with. Boys and girls. And the girls were as much tomboys - they would join in - in - in the sports as good as the boys.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would you play with on the whole, your brothers, sisters or neighbours or everybody in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Everybody, we would always be - more or less
 of a gang - that would - join in and - well - it's very seldom that we - would be - we wouldn't be without company.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The mountains were above, that used to give plenty of - of scope, we used to go to the mountains. Then we wo
uld have - the collieries were coming then, and - you could always - on the siding of a colliery there were trams to be pulled, and - the colliery stables, they were a magnet for the boys of the village. The river of course in summer during bathing time. 
There was a variety of - everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you play in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, we would play in the street because - they had the light. Especially in the winter time there was a light in - in the street. And that would afford the - the children - to - fool about round the light.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you play in other children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5178564\charrsid6557717 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 s homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, very seldom. The - if you take the average of the families at that time you would find that there was the average of six or seven in a family. Well - there was no room for
 outsiders, when the family were congregated. And - some of the older boys, of the - of my friends would very soon remind you that it was out, your place was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You mentioned earlier the sort of games that you played, were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
The only game that would - we played football - that would make us dirty - but it was the - the unforgivable thing was to tear your clothes. You could if you got dirty with mud, remember so many times going into a stream, and having a ha
ndful of fern and - brushing the mud off. Never mattered that your clothes were - wet, as long as they were presentable to go -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. There was - don't remember - any restriction ever put in our way to play with who we liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Your parents didn't discourage you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 There came the Boy Scouts - to the place, but it never - caught on. Radicalism - and after that the Labour Party came. T
he - Boy Scouts - was more or less - connected - with the Anglican church. And being there were so few - of those - therefore there were few Boy Scouts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You didn't join?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You didn't think of joining?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you spend your
 free time when you were at school, did you have any hobbies, you mentioned that Friday night and Saturday when you were in school you were working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Working, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So you didn't have all that free time, you mentioned that you were playing and you used to fish, and you had a bike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. The -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you garden or anything like that or collect anything or keep a pet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, we kept - I always kept a rabbit. A rabbit or two. And - they were just the angora type of - white rabbits with p
ink - pink eyes. And - oh I had - quite a lot of fun with - with the rabbits. And it taught me one thing, to have - the care for - something else. You cannot keep a pet without - we always had - had a cat. And I can always remember my father saying, when 
h
e - a new little tom cat would come, and we wanted to have a name on it. And he would say, well we'll call this cat Sam. I failed to have one of my children called after me so I'll call the tom cat. So - Sam, invariably they - the cat, if he was a tom cat
, was called Sam.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You mentioned that you went fishing and you went walking and bicycling? Who would you go with? Your father took you fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about walking and bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Anybody that had the - that had a - a boneshaker, a 
bike, and - although the train passed - we would go to Aberafon by train but never - anybody thought of going to Neath by train, because you could walk - to Neath in the time it would take you to get by train. So - those bikes were useful to go to Neath -
 and by going to Neath of course we could see - football matches of a class - higher than we - although we had a team - in the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about Neath Fair, that used to be a big thing didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh Neath Fair, we used to look forward to Neath 
Fair. And - my first recollection of Neath Fair, was as a boy - and going down under a bridge, I must have been about nine - nine or ten, and - had a passion for horses, and on the morning of Neath Fair - from eight o'clock - onwards, you would see these 
comin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 g because - farmers used to wal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
k - ride their horses or lead them - from Maesteg over the Bryn, the - Avon Valley as gar as Glyn Corog, they would all brought - bring their horses down past our village, Pontrhydyfen, and then walk them to Neath. So - w
e would ask if a man was - riding one pony himself, and leading two, we would ask if we could sit on one of the - and were allowed to go to Neath. So I can remember now the string of horses by the Cross Keys, from the Cross Keys - right along the road, an
d
 these gipsies and dealers and farmers - and the shouting and the - well quite a lot but we - had to walk back afterwards, there were no horses going back. So there was an old saying - I'm as tired as a dog having been to the fair. Well that's how we felt
 after Neath fair, oh - that was the Thursday, Thursday the Neath Fair, the horse fair. But - Saturday - it wasn't until I had started working - that I could sport a shilling in my pocket that I could go to - that's what it was termed, the Fool's Fair.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you go to any theatres when you were still at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No theatre, the theatre hadn't come but there had come the living pictures, down - at Carmarthen. Eblies. And it was at the time when Tom Mix was the hero, Pearl White as Pearl of the Army, 
and these - well they were thrills but we could only afford to go - to the matinees on Saturday afternoon where we could have the entrance for tuppence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you go often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, not often other than - every - Saturday matinee, and that is when we
 could afford it. When we could afford the time between the - delivering the - goods for the grocer and - but it wasn't 'til later on that the - we would go to the - to an evening session, but always walking down and walking back. And - three miles.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, took part in football - as soon as I could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you go to music hall at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, we came there again the - the village was divided - into two parts as far as the children were concerned. Now it was a
t that time that the influx of English people came, following English managers to the different collier, we did have people from the Forest of Dene, and we did have people from the Monmouth Valleys. Names came by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 H}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 owdels, the Friars, the Wheelers, they cam
e - but what was surprising in our village - we did not condescend to speak English - to these newcomers. They were absorbed - they had to absorb into our - into our community, the children learnt Welsh and they are still Welsh, and the ones in the collie
r
y, they learnt Welsh - sufficient to have a - a - a reasonable working - grip of the language, but - they had different - they spent their leisure differently. Whereas the native of Pontrhydyfen, the Welsh non-conformist child - would think of the events 
i
n Neath - or the music hall in Port Talbot as something - well, terrible. But these young - English people, the Howdells, the Wheelers, and the Friars, they as children went to the music hall, and I can always remember with a thrill how they, for the firs
t time, brought back the rag times, and the rag time was something - and - well we soon started to jig to that, but that was the first introduction - of the music hall to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You didn't go yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. It's - I can't remember going to the Vince at all - not as a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But you went to the cinema?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, if you were without. If you were without - but as I have mentioned - from very early on I - was more or less self-maintaining in
 - pocket money. But I wouldn't be - I wouldn't be - short, except for one - and this one - I will never forgive my parents, there came a circus - I've said that. I couldn't go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You still feel it really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I - there you are, but I have come to know after that that there was not a pennies to be had to spare then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 They wouldn't have minded you going to the circus?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Just didn't have the money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Because you would all have had to go I expect if you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh no, that wasn't again you 
couldn't - that wasn't the rule, if - if my parents thought that - one of the members, never mind who it was, deserved to go - it didn't make any difference - it was there for him to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You said you spent a lot of your pocket money on Woodbines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, to anything that was going we could - and of course we came after the football matches were coming and - more popular, and you would have to take unless there was a hole in the fence of the field - a - you have a copper to go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, very seldom after we became - there was always somebody - or if it - it didn't matter if we just closed the door - I don't know that it was ever closed - because - anybody - oh 
somebody would say she had called but there was nobody in, the door was open and - that was the - the measure of trust between - the community.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What would happen if your mother was ill or confined to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 My mother was one of those that was endowed with - her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
ary migraine. Migraine and if she - suffered all her life with that. And it was nothing new for us as children - that my mother would be with - a - a cloth around her forehead and that had been soaked in v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 negar, and she would be lying on the couch and there this migrai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 e - migraine would have been - but at though - at that time we would all rally round. From my father to every member of the family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would any of your neighbours come in and help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not during the period of 
a migraine. But I do remember the epidemic - the flu epidemic that came - after was it 1919? 18. Just - it was very serious. And I can always remember that time, we as a family were all of us - practically down - I can remember my brother and I were in th
e
 same bed - and - my aunts were coming then, even though one was a headmistress - but she was passing and doing what she could. Until somebody came better, but - what I can remember about that epidemic - when we - when we did - get better, we started to p
e
rspire. The doctor was coming and - it was a dose of quinine - that was the only thing that was given. And then we, my brother and I started to sweat, to perspire at the same time. And that's the first time - I ever remember - the bedclothes soaking with 
perspiration. But after that was - after that experience, the - flu - the influenza would leave us and - but only on an epidemic like that would anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember what happened when one of your younger brothers or sisters was born? How did your mother manage then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh there was a girl coming in at that time. It had been prearranged - prearranged that - of course the washerwoman, Mrs Cullis, would come in - that day - but there were - I - I remember - three or four girls, who would be with ma
m - about a day before, the child was born for about a fortnight, three weeks afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Stay there all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, they - no, no, they wouldn't stay the night. They would - just come in the morning, and - go in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they be someone that your mother paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes, they were - they were my cousins on my father's side - they were older than we were, and - one I - she's still alive, I can remember - she would not drink tea, she wouldn't drink anything - only Van Houten's 
cocoa. And wherever she went, even on her honeymoon, she took a tin of Van Houtens cocoa with her, and still - it is Van Houtens cocoa if she can get it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Your parents did have relatives living nearby, your mother's family were all in Pontrhydyfen weren't they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And your father's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And as many as they were, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh in and out, in and out all - well - they never would be a week that we wouldn't see - see them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes. Quite a lot of friends. And - there's one thing - one incident I can remember. I must have been a little urchin about seven. And on a Saturday afternoon before Christmas, I was playing with the rest on - on the field by the house, and t
he man - came by, from the colliery, so he - told me to go and tell my mother to get me ready - to go and catch the four o'clock train. Well I got ready and the man called for me, and took, me to Swansea. First time I'd ever been to - Swansea on the night
 before Christmas. And I must have been just at that time that the - Woolworth's stores were introduced, the stores with nothing costing more than sixpence. I can remember the man taking me into Masters, and having a pair of gloves, the first}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 pair of gloves
 I had ever had, I - well - just that trip - and it was so valuable because it was so unexpected, and - I always remember that man. Who were friends of my father and mother, and who - gave me that treat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your father and mother have the same friends? Or did your mother have friends of her own and your father have friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh I would say who were friends of my mother's were friends of my father and vice versa. There were no distinctions like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where would they see their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
They would always see them in chapel. And they would always see them in - in the various functions that would go such as concerts or - eistedfoods. And that type of thing, but they - later on when it came that we had a memorial hall, there was m
ore use of the friendships then, they became - more together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Not formally. No. Everybody would be given well - if you're passing, call and - they weren't issuing - invitations as such, call and you'd be welcome.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would people call?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, they would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 For instance, my - some people - would never pass, they - they were - \{BLANK\}
 they would say, and felt that they were constrained to call - rather than pass. And how often - however often they - would pass they would call.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
As soon as they came into the house - that's the first thing a man - would come in, he'd be invited to sit down, and the iron kettle was put on the fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they come on any particular days or occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, if it was - well if it was somebody had been to Neath Fair, and - well - I've been to the fair and - at that time used to go - to go to Neath - to buy the pig, and - if you were lucky or I remember carrying a pig - a piglet - back in a s}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ck. Yes. And - there you are, bring back just little - a little winner and carry him all the way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you say that the friends invited in were your mother's friends or your father's friends, or friends of both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Friends of the both. Friends of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about neighbours, would they come in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. The neighbours were in and out - many times a day. Living as we were one side of the big bridg
e, the bridge in Pontrhydyfen, anybody passing over the bridge would - would be seen. And - well you see somebody going midday, and - one of the neighbours or my mother would say, well, it's strange to see him this time of day. And would go next door to s
a
y, well - I wonder what's happened there. And I would either see him turning towards the station to go by train, or turning over and you knew he was going to the surgery to see the doctor and - they would ferret out - the reason for any - unusual happenin
g.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not by invite. Not - special invite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 But they'd pop in and out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes. Unless there was a - unless there was an illness or there was - somebody having had a colliery accide
nt. They would be very faithful in their visitations then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends? Or with their neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh mostly 
they - they were influenced then - by story telling. Story telling was - had been worked to a fine art. And - they - my parents and many more in the village had come under the influence of the literature of Daniel Owen, and Rhys Lewis and Gwen Thomas, and
 books like the \{BLANK\}
 And those were - they knew them off by heart. And - they would always refer to something that Mary Lewis would have said - or Thomas Bartley would have said - then they would discuss such things as - as that or the - whatever literar
y - book or - a new book that was coming out or if there was a new literary star appearing in the heaven they'd know about it, and that was their - medium of discussion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was there music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, there were music. And if it would go musical in our h
ouse the violin would - my father would have the violin out. And - well we had - referring back again to the - 1914 war - when the boys came back from the war and every Friday night there was a smoking concert in the hall - in Pontrhydyfen And - there the
 solos, there was new solos coming out, and my sister, my eldest sister, she was a very good singer, my father was a very good tenor and the violinist so they would be preparing - preparing for those concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would they play cards or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. Cards were considered the devil's - cards in - never remember a pack of cards being played in our house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging t
o one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes. There were divisions then. The divisions - with the children, were in their mode of clothing - some people - they were poor, they were too poor to have - new clothes, but what clothes they had were very heavily patc
hed and clean. Those were the poor people - who were poor by circumstances. There were poor people also - some of these people who had come to the place from other places, and whose parents - at least their father, was spending too much time in the public
 houses, and that family would suffer. Now there - there was a distinction between - the poor people - who were poor for no fault of their own. And the people who were impoverished by their own excesses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were they the only differences in Pontrhydyfen, or do you think there were other groups or classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well I've mentioned the classes that - the Anglican church brought which clung more to the establishment than did the non-conformists - that name comes very very - the - the ones that would not con
firm, and they were very very much in evidence. They were - divided in that part.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Which class of group would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well I believe there were - there was a - a - an upper class and a lower class. And of course - societ
y - graded our family - in the upper class, in as much that we - my father was a manager. He commanded more respect than the ordinary - and we were expected as a family, to live up - to a standard that was - well, we had to conform to the standard that we
 were placed in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did that affect you as a little boy, would you have felt that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, I felt that very very much when - during the 19 - 12 miners strike, the minimum wage strike. Then I was nine and in school, and the soup kitchen were opened - op
ened to children. And they were coming to school with their basins. But - my mother's family, there were a few teachers in - in them and one or two colliery managers then, apart from my - my uncle was a colliery manager, and - they had resolved that their
 grandchildren weren't going to go to the soup kitchen, and I can remember crying - and defying my mother and taking a basin and going to the soup kitchen, but that was family pride more than anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You wanted to be like the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were all the children going or were there many that were not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well - there were some - who would rather die - than send their children to the soup kitchen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What sort of people belonged to the same group as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh the up
per class of the village were - you could know them by their clothes. By their - mode of living. And - they were freer I should think, they - anybody who was free that could look a grocer in the eyes and - but there were those that couldn't help but go in
to debt, and they more or less branded themselves. The haves - and the haves not, you had them back there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
You mentioned the other sort of people that belonged in the other classes, can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh no. That was - absolutely forbidden in the house. If - if you were - known to have - shown any - any - preference to somebody because he was of your class, to the detriment of somebody who was less fortunate, then you would - that was not tolerated.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you ever told to touch your cap or show respect in some way to anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, we weren't taught that the - well I don't know that I had a cap very often to touch - to anybody. We would acknowledge - we would ackn
owledge the - headmaster - but otherwise I don't remember acknowledging anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was there anyone you called sir or master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 In the teaching profession, only the ones that were - our -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in that way, curtseying or toughing their cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Only - an occasional - labourer in the colliery, who would come after - if he had been out of work and was looking for a job - I've seen those coming to the house cap in hand - I didn't like it, neither d
id my father like it. So he usually just treated them as - and if there was a job and they would have it, and those people who - well for years afterwards - not only thanked themselves but made their children and - yes, this is my special friend, he helpe
d me. I can remember that in a few cases.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 In the district where you lived who were considered the most important people then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The minister. The ministers were - number one. There was a - respect for the deacons held - were held in - high esteem. 
The schoolteachers - they graded themselves - some of them were very popular, some were not popular. But - after that - the doctor of course, the medical doctor - he commanded our respect. But afterwards, if he was a working man - I don't think there was 
any - any - special -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you come into contact with them, you would the teachers and the ministers wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Why were they considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The minister - we were taught - to - the reverence - of the minister - position
, and his family, they were the people of - children of the Manse, or the - min - well that - in itself - well then the - deacons, so often - were our Sunday school teachers. And then - the few that we had - as - every day - teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, the shopkeepers were not - they were not special, they were just - treated as everybody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who did they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well the shopkeepers were - just members of the society, can quite remember them - they were members of th
e - chapel, they would join in everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the clergy then, who did they mix with or associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No, the clergy at that time - had to cater - for a growing need. Of - an intellectual community. And they did not have much time - th
ey spent more time in their study - than they do today. So - they - were aloof, and they kept apart, that's my experience of the clergy then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Teachers were - of course - the boys especially the ones that had been to university - they i
ntroduced a new something - that was athletics. We admired their power as - athletics, and the different branches of athletics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the farmers in the area, who would they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The farmers in the area were - not considered very
 - high in the social list. True there were not many of them. But - they had - nothing to give - nothing to give, they always wanted to sell. And - and therefore they were a race apart, and - somebody that you had to bargain with, for everything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about employers? Of course your father really was an employer wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. Well now we remember - we remember some employers - the Gibbs - he was - in the small colliery owner, well the family of the Jacob's - Percy Jacob, Fred Jacob, they were 
the pioneers of the Avon Valley, and - they had everybody - respected them very very much, and you had - Llewellyn Howell, Herbert Hudson, now those people - we knew - that - we depended so much upon them for our livelihood, that they were - special membe
rs of our respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they mix with the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Very seldom. Very - very seldom we - we as ordinary people didn't come in contact with those. The only thing we knew about them was their contact with - my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living, or would you say there were different groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
It was more or less uniform - the - the village did not cater - did not cater for - anything, everything that was in the Co-operative - was fo
r the higher middle class or the lower middle class it was there. The only part where the distinction became known - was when it became holiday time. Now holidays - were - taken then - the people that could afford - to go to the Wells for a week - there w
e
re some of my aunts - some of my uncles - who were saving up for this luxury. And - I can remember the time when - I also used to - save up - save up for two years after I had - been working in the colliery, to have a week's holiday in Aberystwyth. And we
 used to pay then two pound five - for board and lodge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 That would be after the war that you would go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, it would - after the war, between - after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you think that any group felt superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, there were. T
here were families - that - who did feel superior. And again I must refer, they were - the establishment, and - the Anglican church goers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would you mean by the establishment?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 The establishment were the people that - would stand up for God 
Save the Queen or Kind and Queen, and - well by going - they - praised the Royal Family and - the big day in school, what is the meaning of Empire Day? Why do the canons roar? Why does the cry God Save the King echo from shore to shore? Now what I mean by
 the establish - people who thought like that. Well whereas - we never - never felt - very much - in that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were some families thought of as rough? And others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, they - there were families who were graded as rough - ruffia
ns. Their mode of work in the collieries very often made them that way. They were people who - followed - hard headings - now they - were hard - tremendous hard workers, they were earning - money driving galleries through rock, but they all suffered from 
it, they all went to an early grave, with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 silicosis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 , for that. But they were - and - reve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 led in the fact that they were the tough roughs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And some were thought of as respectable were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, there was families who were more genteel. Little
 girls in school from the beginning - but I think that was - hereditary - endowed on them, you'd have a little girl who was very genteel, and she'd remain so all her life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes. That was - that mark of distinction, and it was very very pronounced in the collieries. You had - a man he couldn't fool, he couldn't fool his fellow men - you were asked if you'd go and ask for a - a - job in the colliery, you were asked - your
 qualifications, could you - put a pair of timber up, what did you know about - this or that, were you acquainted with this seam or no? Well if you said yes - and you were employed on those terms but if you were found deficient - then - it was pity help y
o
u, you were out. And again with the - power of men - they - the best craftsmen were chosen to be - heading - the people that were driving the main galleries. Now this meant a little - well not - I - it meant much more skill than the ordinary men. For inst
a
nce he had to - you had to work - to a survey. And that's best explained by saying I remember - driving the main gallery, the main deep - in Aberboyden colliery, and was told on a Wednesday, you've got to stop. Why, what's the matter? Oh there is a disput
e
 - about the field up on Llangenud which was - miles away seemingly, but - the question of way leave - and the owner of that land up - on the mountain, would be demanding a way leave for the coal that was passing under. Therefore - it was so important tha
t everyone of these galleries was driven direct to point, and sometimes driven to avoid paying way leave to another landlord. Therefore - the heading men, and the deep men were a class above the ordinary collier.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What about the labourers, the ordinary colliers were just sort of labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, there was a distinction between the labourer afterwards and the - collier. The labourer was - wasn't expected - to have any more tools than - a shovel. Maybe - a pick. But never a mandrel. A mandrel was for 
cutting coal, and a pick would - do many things. But - the collier - he only had to be proficient in cutting coal, and to protect himself by putting posts. He had nothing to do - with the drilling of the rock and the firing and - that business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, they did, class distinction - was - not thought of. We've just said a lot about Sunday school - about Bible classes and so forth, well in the teachings of St Paul and al
l those, you are taught - that there were to be no distinctions, and anybody that would create distinctions after was hypocrity - hypocritical, and - I don't think that ever applied.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You don't think your mother saw herself as a particular class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another? Do you remember anyone who did? There were labouring classes weren't there and there were the upper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, it - you would - but we would not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 create}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717  that. I'll give an example in
 this way. When we moved down to Oak - Kenfig Hill, all the officials of the colliery - were housed in - a series of houses - ten families. The first two - were double fronted, and - they had bay windows up and down, with a garden, an extensive garden. On
e
 belonged to the agent and the other to the manager. Well there were two gardeners employed by the company to see to those gardens and everything the wants of the families. Well then you had the - electricians and the mechanics, and - those for the two co
l
lieries in the other houses. That's the first time I saw - the distinction - in trades And it was very surprising - the agents wife and my mother - were bosom friends, and when these - people were so subservient and coming and cow towing, they laughed at 
that - because - not one of them - liked servility. It hurt I believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, yes, there was the real gentleman, you cannot - the real gentleman cannot - disguise - that aspect of him.
 His deportment. His - mode of - dressing. His salutation to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember anybody being described as a real gentleman in Pontrhydyfen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. There were - three or four of them, that had come to the place, and had - continued - on the s
ame even keel as when they came there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 They were people who were - commercial travel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 ers. Commercial travellers, maybe it was part of their make up to go and - but they never forgot it. And people who were - agents for differe
nt firms, they would visit you, and you felt that - that you were addressing a real gentleman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 ny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 one described as a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes. They had those - the wives - of these sometime. Again, there were - these young girls - that 
had gone - and - they had gone to do war work especially nursing. And they came to - they had been to London, they had been to different places, and when they came back, there was that deportment with them, and it never left them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember seeing a policeman around when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes, the bobby. A bobby was - a character - to be respected. To be - but I never have had - any much experience in my youth. They would walk the village. Very very seldom - that they were called upon - in my time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did you think of the policeman when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
The policeman that I can remember - were - if you went very close to them they - always smelt of strong drink. Yes. Yes. I can remember the four of them, and - they were - visitors - to the - public houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How do you think the policeman treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well it - it - they treated the people as - that again where the distinction came in. People were then summonsed for debt. There was no sympathy for the de
btor. No sympathy for them. My own experience - the - policeman came to our house more than once with a summons - for my mother to apart - to appear - on my behalf for delinquency - for the truancy in school. If you - if the attendance officer then - if h
e
 - would prosecute - decide to prosecute, and I was to play truant when sheep shearing and sheep washing, or - that type of work was going on in the farm, and I'd lose school for about fortnight to three weeks. And then at the end of that there would be a
 summons. But the fine was the same every time, and that was five shilling. But it was my mother that had to appear before the petty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 sectional}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717  court.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were your mother and father willing for you to lose school like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh they wouldn't - they -
 were against it absolutely, but - there you are, I was - I was insisting on going, and that's what helped in the end - to get - my ticket to leave from school at the age of thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 You said earlier your home was not rented, they bought it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Bought it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
If they did they never showed it. They never showed it at all, we - looking back at life I don't think really that they did. But - once they had gone into the n
ew house - and after the strike, the minimum wage strike and my father was in - as - worked as an official, that the - momentum just - went on and kept on going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Your father wasn't ill or out of work was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. Luckily - we were a - we were 
a very healthy family on - as a whole. And - up - until the fatal illness of my father which lasted about - eight months, I don't remember any prolonged sickness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What difference did it make to you as a family if he was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh as an official it didn't mean anything at all, an official could be - he could be away for a fortnight but his wages would come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 So you didn't ever get help from the Guardians or the Parish or anything like that? When there was someone in the district t
hat the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it? You hear of people being driven out of the district.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I didn't experience - I didn't experience that, they - they were pretty compassionate - to everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were you given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor or a governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When did you go to school, how old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 We weren't admitted I don't think until we were five, to the infants school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 When you first started what time in the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 And when did you come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Nine 'til twelve. And from - half past one - until quarter to four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What kind of school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 There was the infants school - a mixed school, mixed classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 It wasn't a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. Board school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 On foot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well it wouldn't take a matter of - ten minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Nobody that I can remember after going to the infants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Your sister was older than you wasn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, she was but - we just - I - they must - maybe have taken us there the first day or so but afterwards we used to come - in companies.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 I liked school - all along, until - well until I got - twelve or so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 forth, and - then of course once I started - going with the farmers, it was then that I - got disgruntled in school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Well of course we had our favourites at that time, and - there was some - who could make the - could make the lesson interesting, and who would not keep to the syllabus, can remember a few of those. And I c
an remember - others - that were - just waiting for the clock to - time to go away. But the - the - the - the one thing that impressed me after leaving - that I can never remember having had - one lesson in English grammar, nor in Welsh grammar. I came fr
om school from standard seven - without knowing anything about grammar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, like manners or tidiness or way of speaking or punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh yes, one of the first things that we had on a Monday morning - the headmaster would come into the room - and he would - say, show your }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 handkerchiefs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
, and each one would have his handkerchief - up. Well on a Monday morning usually they were clean. But - I can remember once having opened my handkerchief 
out, and there was a hole in it, and this headmaster ridiculing me, and putting this handkerchief, putting the - his stick - through the hole and exhibiting it to the - much to my mother's concern - consternation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How did you feel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well, she was
 only - restrained - but then again you see, the headmaster was an Anglican and there was that - he wouldn't have done that with a - a - he wouldn't - had the hole been twice as big, in one of his flock, or his favourites, there were the favourites then.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Oh yes, that was very very evident - I - it was evident with the Anglican teachers and the headmaster. And it was also evident with the Baptist - as - compared with - Calv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 nistic Methodist. They did have their distinctions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Was it because they were in a minority, because there were far more Methodists than anything weren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, and it was that - I think that it was - the success of the - Calv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 i}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 nistic Methodist - over all the denominations. The children of the Calv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6450268\charrsid6557717 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 nistic Methodist - could sit a written examination, a paper on scripture every year and it was not known with the others nor ever attempted.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Oh it was the cane straight - it was no hesitation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would girls have it as well as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Yes, they would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 What would you have to do to have the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Well, trivialities sometime but - sometime it wouldn't take you 
- inattention would - give you one crack with the tail - with the cane. For being rough and - smudge your book, you'd qualify for two. But if you were fighting in the yard as often - happened, often very - that qualified for four. And I do remember - the 
-
 my - the other one that was fighting, I do remember him having the fifth, for being the vanquished. Because this teacher - this teacher had been watching the fight, but he had to punish for fighting. Well he must have read about old Robin Soldier in - th
e book of - Rhys Lewis, because he used to do the same, but I remember it once in my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 In mine not - so much - I was ordinary, I never was the top of the list. But I never was much further do
wn then the fifth, fourth and fifth. And as such we used to have report - but I didn't like to meet that one very often because - I - when conduct was coming - could - more could be desired. And such - such remarks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did your parents ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Not often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 They were allowed to visit on St David's Day, only.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did they meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. They didn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Most of them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes. There was. That was the geographical - that's what accounted for that. You had - a group from Aneybourhan, which was on the Margam side of the river. Across the river you 
had a group from LLegraw. They were very clannish together. Then you had the Oakwood group, the Pontrhydyfen group, and then the Twyn y Pandy, Carrig Llwydn and Efeail Fach. Now they were - those would - because they travelled to school together, they wou
ld form into distinct - groups.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Not - not by design. Some were - some would isolate themselves - feeling of - inferiority - in games or - they would be the lookers on - wouldn't join in. But - they were the insecure children, mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you go on to another school afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 No. Only the one school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 At thirteen - thirteen, fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
No, I wouldn't. I - I - will admit - that after I had been - working underground - for six months - and knew what it was to - fill carts - in the height of - two foot two, and knocking your elbows, and my head, I did regret that I had - left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Did you attend any part time education afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15352313 JE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 
Yes, later I - the - mining and geology class - courses for night school. They were very good classes and - we followed those, up until the fifth year which - gave us a very very good grounding in mathematics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14483652 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid489342\charrsid6557717 Do you have any regrets about your education?
