rom a generation - of few generations of colliers, I cultivate a keen - sense of hearing, you can hear things, it's bred into you. And we were on this coal face, and - you had the trays and the clatter of this iron conveyor working, I heard something. So 
I
 stopped the conveyor. Then I - what's the matter? Anyway I started up again. I heard it a second time and I stopped it. So my mates impatient said - Jack Edward's got the wind up. Yes, I said, I've got the wind up and he's going out. And I got hold of my
 
clothes, my cap and away. But I hadn't gone very far before the rest followed me in a great hurry, and that conveyor and the coal cutter, the lot were buried under thousands of tons of a fall. That never felt - after mechanical - I was never satisfied But
 
it came on - the church came in - sometime later - that - a head - under - manager who was very very officious, and he - insisted - that - we should walk - to stages, and I refused, being it was uphill, and we had to walk to catch the workman's spake, tha
t
's the journey that went on, and I refused. So he - said, all right, he'd go without me. Very well, I said, but don't forget, I know the coalmines act, and with these boys under our care we are it's against the act to do so. So the following morning he - 
w
hen I came to work, he came to try - he used to like to make an example of somebody, if he had a good audience. In front of the men. But that was the biggest mistake he ever did, because he had - more than he bargained for. I did go down - to the colliery
,
 but only to get the hatchet and the sledge, and - went home and asked the manager to - give me my cards, and I had decided to finish in the colliery. England were playing Wales in Twickenham, on the Saturday. So I bid my mother farewell, and the colliery
