 and went up to see the match in Twickenham. That was in 1930. Well the - having gone I just wondered - my mother had told me, well you've thrown your job - you are not sure of having a job. But the train left Pyle at seven, and - got to - Paddington - qu
a
rter past eleven. They were building the - flats in New Bond Street at the time, some building going up, I walked in. I asked, any chance for a job? And he asked me, labouring? I said, yes. Well we finish at twelve, he gave me a green card. And he said, c
ome back Monday morning by eight o'clock and within half an hour I had had a job in London. However I went down to the -
